# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: children-s-hospital
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Puberty is a period of several years in which rapid physical growth and psychological changes occur, culminating in sexual maturity.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] The average age of onset of puberty is 10–11 for girls and 11–12 for boys.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Every person's individual timetable for puberty is influenced primarily by heredity, although environmental factors, such as diet and exercise, also exert some influences.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] These factors can also contribute to precocious and delayed puberty.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Some of the most significant parts of pubertal development involve distinctive physiological changes in individuals' height, weight, body composition, and circulatory and respiratory systems.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] These changes are largely influenced by hormonal activity.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Hormones play an organizational role, priming the body to behave in a certain way once puberty begins, and an active role, referring to changes in hormones during adolescence that trigger behavioral and physical changes.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Puberty occurs through a long process and begins with a surge in hormone production, which in turn causes a number of physical changes.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] This is triggered by the pituitary gland, which secretes a surge of hormonal agents into the blood stream, initiating a chain reaction.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] The male and female gonads are thereby activated, which puts them into a state of rapid growth and development; the triggered gonads now commence mass production of hormones.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] The testes primarily release testosterone, and the ovaries predominantly dispense estrogen.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] The production of these hormones increases gradually until sexual maturation is met.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Some boys may develop gynecomastia due to an imbalance of sex hormones, tissue responsiveness or obesity.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Facial hair in males normally appears in a specific order during puberty: The first facial hair to appear tends to grow at the corners of the upper lip, typically between 14 and 16 years of age.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] It then spreads to form a moustache over the entire upper lip.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] This is followed by the appearance of hair on the upper part of the cheeks, and the area under the lower lip.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] The hair eventually spreads to the sides and lower border of the chin, and the rest of the lower face to form a full beard.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] As with most human biological processes, this specific order may vary among some individuals.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Facial hair is often present in late adolescence, around ages 17 and 18, but may not appear until significantly later.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Some men do not develop full facial hair for 10 years after puberty.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Facial hair continues to get coarser, much darker, and thicker for another 2–4 years after puberty.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] The major landmark of puberty for males is spermarche, the first ejaculation, which occurs, on average, at age 13.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] For females, it is menarche, the onset of menstruation, which typically occurs around age 13, plus or minus two or three years.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] The age of menarche is influenced by heredity, but a girl's diet and lifestyle contribute as well.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Regardless of genes, a girl must have a certain proportion of body fat to attain menarche.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Consequently, girls who have a high-fat diet and who are not physically active begin menstruating earlier, on average, than girls whose diet contains less fat and whose activities involve fat reducing exercise (e.g. ballet and gymnastics).
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Girls who experience malnutrition or are in societies in which children are expected to perform physical labor also begin menstruating at later ages.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] The timing of puberty can have important psychological and social consequences.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Early maturing boys are usually taller and stronger than their friends.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] They have the advantage in capturing the attention of potential partners and in being picked first for sports.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Pubescent boys often tend to have a good body image, are more confident, secure, and more independent.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Late maturing boys can be less confident because of poor body image when comparing themselves to already developed friends and peers.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] However, early puberty is not always positive for boys; early sexual maturation in boys can be accompanied by increased aggressiveness due to the surge of hormones that affect them.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Because they appear older than their peers, pubescent boys may face increased social pressure to conform to adult norms; society may view them as more emotionally advanced, despite the fact that their cognitive and social development may lag behind their appearance.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Studies have shown that early maturing boys are more likely to be sexually active and are more likely to participate in risky behaviors.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] For girls, early maturation can sometimes lead to increased self-consciousness, a typical aspect in maturing females.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Because of their bodies' developing in advance, pubescent girls can become more insecure and dependent.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Consequently, girls that reach sexual maturation early are more likely than their peers to develop eating disorders (such as anorexia nervosa and bulimia nervosa).
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Nearly half of all American high school girls' diets are to lose weight.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] In addition, girls may have to deal with sexual advances from older boys before they are emotionally and mentally mature.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Early-maturing girls may date earlier than late-maturing girls, and so have earlier sexual experiences and more unwanted pregnancies.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Earlier-maturing girls are more exposed to alcohol and drug abuse.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Those who have had such experiences tend to not perform as well in school as their "inexperienced" peers.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Girls have usually reached full physical development around ages 15–17, while boys usually complete puberty around ages 16–17.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Any increase in height beyond the post-pubertal age is uncommon.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Girls attain reproductive maturity about four years after the first physical changes of puberty appear.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] In contrast, boys develop more slowly but continue to grow for about six years after the first visible pubertal changes.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] The physical development of girls during their teenage years can be broken down into three distinct stages.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] At the start, which generally coincides with the beginning of rapid growth, there is the development of breast buds and pubic hair.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] The peak period of physical growth occurs approximately one year later in concert with stage two of sexual maturity.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Approximately 1 to 1.6 years after the onset of secondary sex characteristics, girls enter into the third stage which typically includes menarche.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] By this time, they will have finished their growth spurt and experience a notable broadening of the hips as well as an adult fat distribution.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Additionally, breast development is complete and hair in both the pubic region and armpits (axillary hair) will be darker and more widespread.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] In comparison to girls, it can be tricky to define when exactly sexual development in boys begins.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] For boys, puberty typically takes around 5 years to finish, as opposed to just 3+1⁄2 years for girls (menarche).
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] By this point in time, they have already experienced their growth spurt and there are evident changes in their body shape – wider hips and fat distribution is more adult-like.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Breast development will also be completed by this stage.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] In boys, four stages in development can be correlated with the curve of general body growth at adolescence.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] The initial sign of sexual maturation in boys usually is the "fat spurt".
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] The maturing boy gains weight and becomes almost chubby, with a somewhat feminine fat distribution.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] This probably occurs because estrogen production by the Leydig cells in the testes is stimulated before the more abundant Sertoli cells begin to produce significant amounts of testosterone.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] During this stage, boys may appear obese and somewhat awkward physically.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Approximately 1 year after the scrotum begins to increase in size, stage II can be seen.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] During this time, there is a redistribution of subcutaneous fat and the start of pubic hair growth.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Following 8 to 12 months of the peak velocity in height gain, stage III ensues.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] This period is marked by an obvious widenening of hips with a more adult-like fat distribution and full development of the breasts.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] All together, these three stages culminate in a complete growth spurt for most individuals.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] At this time, axillary hair appears and facial hair appears on the upper lip only.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] A spurt in muscle growth also occurs, along with a continued decrease in subcutaneous fat and an obviously harder and more angular body form.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Pubic hair distribution appears more adult but has not yet spread to the medial area of the thighs.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] The penis and scrotum are near adult size.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Stage IV for boys, which occurs anywhere from 15 to 24 months after stage III, is difficult to pinpoint.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] At this time, the spurt of growth in height ends.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] There is facial hair on the chin and the upper lip, adult distribution and color of pubic and axillary hair, and a further increase in muscular strength.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] The adolescent growth spurt is a rapid increase in the individual's height and weight during puberty resulting from the simultaneous release of growth hormones, thyroid hormones, and androgens.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Males experience their growth spurt about two years later, on average, than females.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] In addition to changes in height, adolescents also experience a significant increase in body mass / weight.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] The weight gained during adolescence constitutes nearly half of one's adult body weight.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Teenage and early adult males may continue to gain natural muscle growth even after puberty.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] The accelerated growth in different body parts happens at different times, but for all adolescents, it has a fairly regular sequence.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] The first places to grow are the extremities—the head, hands and feet—followed by the arms and legs, then the torso and shoulders.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] This non-uniform growth is one reason why an adolescent body may seem out of proportion.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] During puberty, bones become harder and more brittle.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] At the conclusion of puberty, the ends of the long bones close during the process called epiphysis.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] There can be ethnic differences in these skeletal changes.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] For example, in the United States, bone density increases significantly more among black than white adolescents, which might account for decreased likelihood of black women developing osteoporosis and having fewer bone fractures there.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Another set of significant physical changes during puberty happen in bodily distribution of fat and muscle.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] This process is different for females and males.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Before puberty, there are nearly no sex differences in fat and muscle distribution; during puberty, boys grow muscle much faster than girls, although both sexes experience rapid muscle development.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] In contrast, though both sexes experience an increase in body fat, the increase is much more significant for girls.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Frequently, the increase in fat for girls happens in their years just before puberty.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] The ratio between muscle and fat among post-pubertal boys is around three to one, while for girls it is about five to four.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] This may help explain sex differences in athletic performance.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Pubertal development also affects circulatory and respiratory systems as an adolescents' heart and lungs increase in both size and capacity.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] These changes lead to increased strength and tolerance for exercise.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Despite some genetic sex differences, environmental factors play a large role in biological changes during adolescence.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] For example, girls tend to reduce their physical activity in preadolescence and may receive inadequate nutrition from diets that often lack important nutrients, such as iron.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] These environmental influences, in turn, affect female physical development.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Primary sex characteristics are those directly related to the sex organs.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] In males, the first stages of puberty involve growth of the testes and scrotum, followed by growth of the penis.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] At the time that the penis develops, the seminal vesicles, the prostate, and the bulbourethral gland also enlarge and develop.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] The first ejaculation of seminal fluid generally occurs about one year after the beginning of accelerated penis growth, although this is often determined culturally rather than biologically, since for many boys the first ejaculation occurs as a result of masturbation.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Boys are generally fertile before they have an adult appearance.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] In females, changes in the primary sex characteristics involve growth of the uterus, vagina, and other aspects of the reproductive system.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Menarche, the beginning of menstruation, is a relatively late development which follows a long series of hormonal changes.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Generally, a girl is not fully fertile until several years after menarche, as regular ovulation follows menarche by about two years.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Unlike males, therefore, females usually appear physically mature before they are capable of becoming pregnant.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Changes in secondary sex characteristics include every change that is not directly related to sexual reproduction.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] In males, these changes involve appearance of pubic, facial, and body hair, deepening of the voice, roughening of the skin around the upper arms and thighs, and increased development of the sweat glands.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] In females, secondary sex changes involve elevation of the breasts, widening of the hips, development of pubic and underarm hair, widening of the areolae, and elevation of the nipples.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] The changes in secondary sex characteristics that take place during puberty are often referred to in terms of five Tanner stages, named after the British pediatrician who devised the categorization system.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] The human brain is not finished developing by the time a person reaches puberty, or even finishes it.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] The frontal lobe of the brain has been known to shape itself well into one's 30s.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Neuroscientists often cannot agree precisely on when this developmental period ends or if there is an exact age for the end of brain development.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Below the age of about roughly 30, the human brain has been implicated in human behavior and social immaturity.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] However, there has been no empirical study indicating a causal relationship with the development of the prefrontal cortex in adolescence and into early adulthood with any irrational behaviors.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] The brain reaches 90% of its adult size by six years of age.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Thus, the brain does not grow in size much during adolescence.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] It is a common misconception that the human brain matures at around age 25 and is immature before that.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Over the course of adolescence, the amount of white matter in the brain increases linearly, while the amount of grey matter in the brain follows an inverted-U pattern.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Through a process called synaptic pruning, unnecessary neuronal connections in the brain are eliminated and the amount of grey matter is pared down.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] However, this does not mean that the brain loses functionality; rather, it becomes more efficient due to increased myelination (insulation of axons) and the reduction of unused pathways.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] The first areas of the brain to be pruned are those involving primary functions, such as motor and sensory areas.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] The areas of the brain involved in more complex processes lose matter later in development.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] These include the lateral and prefrontal cortices, among other regions.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Some of the most developmentally significant changes in the brain occur in the prefrontal cortex, which is involved in decision making and cognitive control, as well as other higher cognitive functions.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] During adolescence, myelination and synaptic pruning in the prefrontal cortex increases, improving the efficiency of information processing, and neural connections between the prefrontal cortex and other regions of the brain are strengthened.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] This leads to better evaluation of risks and rewards, as well as improved control over impulses.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Specifically, developments in the dorsolateral prefrontal cortex are important for controlling impulses and planning ahead, while development in the ventromedial prefrontal cortex is important for decision making.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Changes in the orbitofrontal cortex are important for evaluating rewards and risks.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Three neurotransmitters that play important roles in adolescent brain development are glutamate, dopamine and serotonin.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Glutamate is an excitatory neurotransmitter.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] During the synaptic pruning that occurs during adolescence, most of the neural connections that are pruned contain receptors for glutamate or other excitatory neurotransmitters.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Because of this, by early adulthood the synaptic balance in the brain is more inhibitory than excitatory.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Dopamine is associated with pleasure and attuning to the environment during decision-making.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] During adolescence, dopamine levels in the limbic system increase and input of dopamine to the prefrontal cortex increases.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] The balance of excitatory to inhibitory neurotransmitters and increased dopamine activity in adolescence may have implications for adolescent risk-taking and vulnerability to boredom (see Cognitive development below).
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Serotonin is a neuromodulator involved in regulation of mood and behavior.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Development in the limbic system plays an important role in determining rewards and punishments and processing emotional experience and social information.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Changes in the levels of the neurotransmitters dopamine and serotonin in the limbic system make adolescents more emotional and more responsive to rewards and stress.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] The corresponding increase in emotional variability also can increase adolescents' vulnerability.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] The effect of serotonin is not limited to the limbic system: Several serotonin receptors have their gene expression change dramatically during adolescence, particularly in the human frontal and prefrontal cortex.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Adolescence is a time of rapid cognitive development.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Piaget describes adolescence as the stage of life in which the individual's thoughts start taking more of an abstract form and the egocentric thoughts decrease, allowing the individual to think and reason in a wider perspective.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] A combination of behavioural and fMRI studies have demonstrated development of executive functions, that is, cognitive skills that enable the control and coordination of thoughts and behaviour, which are generally associated with the prefrontal cortex.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] The thoughts, ideas and concepts developed at this period of life greatly influence one's future life, playing a major role in character and personality formation.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Biological changes in brain structure and connectivity within the brain interact with increased experience, knowledge, and changing social demands to produce rapid cognitive growth (see Changes in the brain above).
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] The age at which particular changes take place varies between individuals, but the changes discussed below begin at puberty or shortly after that and some skills continue to develop as the adolescent ages.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] The dual systems model proposes a maturational imbalance between development of the socioemotional system and cognitive control systems in the brain that contribute to impulsivity and other behaviors characteristic of adolescence.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Some studies like the ABCD Study are researching on the baseline of adolescent cognitive development.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] There are at least two major approaches to understanding cognitive change during adolescence.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] One is the constructivist view of cognitive development.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Based on the work of Piaget, it takes a quantitative, state-theory approach, hypothesizing that adolescents' cognitive improvement is relatively sudden and drastic.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] The second is the information-processing perspective, which derives from the study of artificial intelligence and attempts to explain cognitive development in terms of the growth of specific components of the thinking process.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] By the time individuals have reached ages 12–14 or so their critical thinking and decision-making competency are comparable to those of adults.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Memory: Improvements are seen in both working memory and long-term memory.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Processing speed: Adolescents think more quickly than children.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Processing speed improves sharply between age five and middle adolescence; it then begins to level off at age 14/15 and does not appear to change between late adolescence and adulthood.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Organization: Adolescents are more aware of their thought processes and can use mnemonic devices and other strategies to think more efficiently.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Metacognition: Improved knowledge of their own thinking patterns increase self-control and social insight.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Studies newer than 2005 indicate that the brain is changing in efficiency well past its twenties, a 'point of maturity' in the twenties is somewhat arbitrary as many important parts of the brain are noted to be mature by 14 or 15, making 'maturity' hard to define and has often been disagreed with.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Prefrontal cortex pruning has been recorded to level off by age 14 or 15, and has been seen to continue as late as into the sixth decade of life.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] White matter is recorded to increase up until around the age of 45, and then it is lost via progressive aging.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Adolescents' thinking is less bound to concrete events than that of children: they can contemplate possibilities outside the realm of what currently exists.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] One manifestation of the adolescent's increased facility with thinking about possibilities is the improvement of skill in deductive reasoning, which leads to the development of hypothetical thinking.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] This provides the ability to plan ahead, see the future consequences of an action and to provide alternative explanations of events.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] It also makes adolescents more skilled debaters, as they can reason against a friend's or parent's assumptions.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Adolescents also develop a more sophisticated understanding of probability.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] The appearance of more systematic, abstract thinking is another notable aspect of cognitive development during adolescence.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] For example, adolescents find it easier than children to comprehend the sorts of higher-order abstract logic inherent in puns, proverbs, metaphors, and analogies.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Their increased facility permits them to appreciate the ways in which language can be used to convey multiple messages, such as satire, metaphor, and sarcasm.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] A third gain in cognitive ability involves thinking about thinking itself, a process referred to as metacognition.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] It often involves monitoring one's own cognitive activity during the thinking process.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Adolescents' improvements in knowledge of their own thinking patterns lead to better self-control and more effective studying.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] It is also relevant in social cognition, resulting in increased introspection, self-consciousness, and intellectualization (in the sense of thought about one's own thoughts, rather than the Freudian definition as a defense mechanism).
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Adolescents are much better able than children to understand that people do not have complete control over their mental activity.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Being able to introspect may lead to two forms of adolescent egocentrism, which results in two distinct problems in thinking: the imaginary audience and the personal fable.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] These likely peak at age fifteen, along with self-consciousness in general.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Related to metacognition and abstract thought, perspective-taking involves a more sophisticated theory of mind.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Adolescents reach a stage of social perspective-taking in which they can understand how the thoughts or actions of one person can influence those of another person, even if they personally are not involved.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Compared to children, adolescents are more likely to question others' assertions, and less likely to accept facts as absolute truths.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Through experience outside the family circle, they learn that rules they were taught as absolute are in fact relativistic.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] They begin to differentiate between rules instituted out of common sense—not touching a hot stove—and those that are based on culturally relative standards (codes of etiquette, not dating until a certain age), a delineation that younger children do not make.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] This can lead to a period of questioning authority in all domains.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Because most injuries sustained by adolescents are related to risky behavior (alcohol consumption and drug use, reckless or distracted driving, unprotected sex), a great deal of research has been done on the cognitive and emotional processes underlying adolescent risk-taking.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] The behavioral decision-making theory proposes that adolescents and adults both weigh the potential rewards and consequences of an action.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] However, research has shown that adolescents seem to give more weight to rewards, particularly social rewards, than do adults.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Research seems to favor the hypothesis that adolescents and adults think about risk in similar ways, but hold different values and thus come to different conclusions.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Some have argued that there may be evolutionary benefits to an increased propensity for risk-taking in adolescence.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] For example, without a willingness to take risks, teenagers would not have the motivation or confidence necessary to leave their family of origin.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] In addition, from a population perspective, there is an advantage to having a group of individuals willing to take more risks and try new methods, counterbalancing the more conservative elements more typical of the received knowledge held by older adults.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Risk-taking may also have reproductive advantages: adolescents have a newfound priority in sexual attraction and dating, and risk-taking is required to impress potential mates.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Research also indicates that baseline sensation seeking may affect risk-taking behavior throughout the lifespan.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Given the potential consequences, engaging in sexual behavior is somewhat risky, particularly for adolescents.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Having unprotected sex, using poor birth control methods (e.g., withdrawal), having multiple sexual partners, and poor communication are some aspects of sexual behavior that increase individual or social risk.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Aspects of adolescents' lives that are correlated with risky sexual behavior include higher rates of parental abuse, and lower rates of parental support and monitoring.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] Related to their increased tendency for risk-taking, adolescents show impaired behavioral inhibition, including deficits in extinction learning.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] This has important implications for engaging in risky behavior such as unsafe sex or illicit drug use, as adolescents are less likely to inhibit actions that may have negative outcomes in the future.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] This phenomenon also has consequences for behavioral treatments based on the principle of extinction, such as cue exposure therapy for anxiety or drug addiction.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p01] It has been suggested that impaired inhibition, specifically extinction, may help to explain adolescent propensity to relapse to drug-seeking even following behavioral treatment for addiction.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] The formal study of adolescent psychology began with the publication of G.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Hall, who was the first president of the American Psychological Association, defined adolescence to be the period of life from ages 14 to 24, and viewed it primarily as a time of internal turmoil and upheaval (*sturm und drang*).
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] This understanding of youth was based on two then-new ways of understanding human behavior: Darwin's evolutionary theory and Freud's psychodynamic theory.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] He believed that adolescence was a representation of our human ancestors' phylogenetic shift from being primitive to being civilized.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Hall's assertions stood relatively uncontested until the 1950s when psychologists such as Erik Erikson and Anna Freud started to formulate their theories about adolescence.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Freud believed that the psychological disturbances associated with youth were biologically based and culturally universal while Erikson focused on the dichotomy between identity formation and role fulfillment.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Even with their different theories, these three psychologists agreed that adolescence was inherently a time of disturbance and psychological confusion.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] The less turbulent aspects of adolescence, such as peer relations and cultural influence, were left largely ignored until the 1980s.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] From the '50s until the '80s, the focus of the field was mainly on describing patterns of behavior as opposed to explaining them.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Jean Macfarlane founded the University of California, Berkeley's Institute of Human Development, formerly called the Institute of Child Welfare, in 1927.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] The institute was instrumental in initiating studies of healthy development, in contrast to previous work that had been dominated by theories based on pathological personalities.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] The studies looked at human development during the Great Depression and World War II, unique historical circumstances under which a generation of children grew up.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] The Oakland Growth Study, initiated by Harold Jones and Herbert Stolz in 1931, aimed to study the physical, intellectual, and social development of children in the Oakland area.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Data collection began in 1932 and continued until 1981, allowing the researchers to gather longitudinal data on the individuals that extended past adolescence into adulthood.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Jean Macfarlane launched the Berkeley Guidance Study, which examined the development of children in terms of their socioeconomic and family backgrounds.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] These studies provided the background for Glen Elder in the 1960s to propose a life course perspective of adolescent development.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Elder formulated several descriptive principles of adolescent development.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] The principle of historical time and place states that an individual's development is shaped by the period and location in which they grow up.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] The principle of the importance of timing in one's life refers to the different impact that life events have on development based on when in one's life they occur.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] In 1984, the Society for Research on Adolescence (SRA) became the first official organization dedicated to the study of adolescent psychology.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Some of the issues first addressed by this group include: the nature versus nurture debate as it pertains to adolescence; understanding the interactions between adolescents and their environment; and considering culture, social groups, and historical context when interpreting adolescent behavior.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Evolutionary biologists like Jeremy Griffith have drawn parallels between adolescent psychology and the developmental evolution of modern humans from hominid ancestors as a manifestation of how "ontogeny recapitulates phylogeny".
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Identity development is a stage in the adolescent life cycle.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] For most, the search for identity begins in the adolescent years.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] During these years, adolescents are more open to "'try[ing] on' different appearances and behaviors" to discover who they are.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] In an attempt to find their identity and discover who they are, adolescents are likely to cycle through a number of identities to find one that suits them best.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Developing and maintaining identity (in adolescent years) is a difficult task due to multiple factors such as family life, environment, and social status.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Empirical studies suggest that this process might be more accurately described as identity development, rather than formation, but confirms a normative process of change in both content and structure of one's thoughts about the self.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] The two main aspects of identity development are self-clarity and self-esteem.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Since choices made during adolescent years can influence later life, high levels of self-awareness and self-control during mid-adolescence will lead to better decisions during the transition to adulthood.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Researchers have used three general approaches to understanding identity development: self-concept, sense of identity, and self-esteem.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] The years of adolescence create a more conscientious group of young adults.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Adolescents pay close attention and give more time and effort to their appearance as their body goes through changes.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Unlike children, teens put forth an effort to look presentable.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] The environment in which an adolescent grows up also plays an important role in their identity development.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Studies done by the American Psychological Association have shown that adolescents with a less privileged upbringing have a more difficult time developing their identity.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] The idea of self-concept is known as the ability of a person to have opinions and beliefs that are defined confidently, consistent and stable.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Early in adolescence, cognitive developments result in greater self-awareness, greater awareness of others and their thoughts and judgments, the ability to think about abstract, future possibilities, and the ability to consider multiple possibilities at once.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] As a result, adolescents experience a significant shift from the simple, concrete, and global self-descriptions typical of young children; as children, they defined themselves solely by physical traits whereas adolescents additionally define themselves based on their values, thoughts, and opinions.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Adolescents can conceptualize multiple "possible selves" that they could become and long-term possibilities and consequences of their choices.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] For many, these distinctions are uncomfortable, but they also appear to motivate achievement through behavior consistent with the ideal and distinct from the feared possible selves.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Further distinctions in self-concept, called "differentiation," occur as the adolescent recognizes the contextual influences on their own behavior and the perceptions of others, and begin to qualify their traits when asked to describe themselves.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Differentiation appears fully developed by mid-adolescence.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Peaking in the 7th-9th grades, the personality traits adolescents use to describe themselves refer to specific contexts, and therefore may contradict one another.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] The recognition of inconsistent content in the self-concept is a common source of distress in these years (see Cognitive dissonance), but this distress may benefit adolescents by encouraging structural development.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Egocentrism in adolescents forms a self-conscious desire to feel important in their peer groups and enjoy social acceptance.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Unlike the conflicting aspects of self-concept, identity represents a coherent sense of self stable across circumstances and including past experiences and future goals.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Everyone has a self-concept, whereas Erik Erikson argued that not everyone fully achieves identity.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Erikson's theory of stages of development includes the identity crisis in which adolescents must explore different possibilities and integrate different parts of themselves before committing to their beliefs.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] He described the resolution of this process as a stage of "identity achievement" but also stressed that the identity challenge "is never fully resolved once and for all at one point in time".
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Adolescents begin by defining themselves based on their crowd membership.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] "Clothes help teens explore new identities, separate from parents, and bond with peers." Fashion plays a major role when it comes to teenagers finding themselves; fashion is always evolving, which corresponds with the evolution of change in the personality of teenagers.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Adolescents attempt to define their identity by consciously styling themselves in different manners to find what best suits them.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Trial and error in matching both their perceived image and the image others respond to and see, allows for the adolescent to grasp an understanding of who they are.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Just as fashion is evolving to influence adolescents, so is the media.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] "Modern life takes place amidst a never-ending barrage of flesh on screens, pages, and billboards." This barrage consciously or subconsciously registers into the mind causing issues with self-image a factor that contributes to an adolescence sense of identity.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Researcher James Marcia developed the current method for testing an individual's progress along these stages.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] His questions are divided into three categories: occupation, ideology, and interpersonal relationships.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Answers are scored based on the extent to which the individual has explored and the degree to which he has made commitments.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Research since reveals self-examination beginning early in adolescence, but identity achievement rarely occurring before age 18.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] The freshman year of college influences identity development significantly, but may actually prolong psychosocial moratorium by encouraging reexamination of previous commitments and further exploration of alternate possibilities without encouraging resolution.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] For the most part, evidence has supported Erikson's stages: each correlates with the personality traits he originally predicted.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Studies also confirm the impermanence of the stages; there is no final endpoint in identity development.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] An adolescent's environment plays a huge role in their identity development.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] While most adolescent studies are conducted on white, middle class children, studies show that the more privileged upbringing people have, the more successfully they develop their identity.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] The forming of an adolescent's identity is a crucial time in their life.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] It has been recently found that demographic patterns suggest that the transition to adulthood is now occurring over a longer span of years than was the case during the middle of the 20th century.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Accordingly, youth, a period that spans late adolescence and early adulthood, has become a more prominent stage of the life course.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] This, therefore, has caused various factors to become important during this development.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Many factors contribute to the developing social identity of an adolescent from commitment, to coping devices, to social media.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] All of these factors are affected by the environment an adolescent grows up in.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] A child from a more privileged upbringing is exposed to more opportunities and better situations in general.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] An adolescent from an inner city or a crime-driven neighborhood is more likely to be exposed to an environment that can be detrimental to their development.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Children that grow up in comparatively stable or affluent suburban communities tend to have more access to activities that can contribute to a more successful identity development.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Sexual orientation has been defined as "an erotic inclination toward people of one or more genders, most often described as sexual or erotic attractions".
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] In recent years, psychologists have sought to understand how sexual orientation develops during adolescence.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Some theorists believe that there are many different possible developmental paths one could take, and that the specific path an individual follows may be determined by their sex, orientation, and when they reached the onset of puberty.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] In 1989, Troiden proposed a four-stage model for the development of homosexual sexual identity.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] The first stage, known as sensitization, usually starts in childhood, and is marked by the child's becoming aware of same-sex attractions.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] The second stage, identity confusion, tends to occur a few years later.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] In this stage, the youth is overwhelmed by feelings of inner turmoil regarding their sexual orientation, and begins to engage in sexual experiences with same-sex partners.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] In the third stage of identity assumption, which usually takes place a few years after the adolescent has left home, adolescents begin to come out to their family and close friends, and assumes a self-definition as gay, lesbian, or bisexual.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] In the final stage, known as commitment, the young adult adopts their sexual identity as a lifestyle.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Therefore, this model estimates that the process of coming out begins in childhood, and continues through the early to mid 20s.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] This model has been contested, and alternate ideas have been explored in recent years.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] In terms of sexual identity, adolescence is when most gay/lesbian and transgender adolescents begin to recognize and make sense of their feelings.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Many adolescents may choose to come out during this period of their life once an identity has been formed; many others may go through a period of questioning or denial, which can include experimentation with both homosexual and heterosexual experiences.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] A study of 194 lesbian, gay, and bisexual youths under the age of 21 found that having an awareness of one's sexual orientation occurred, on average, around age 10, but the process of coming out to peers and adults occurred around age 16 and 17, respectively.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Coming to terms with and creating a positive LGBT identity can be difficult for some youth for a variety of reasons.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Peer pressure is a large factor when youth who are questioning their sexuality or gender identity are surrounded by heteronormative peers and can cause great distress due to a feeling of being different from everyone else.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] While coming out can also foster better psychological adjustment, the risks associated are real.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Indeed, coming out in the midst of a heteronormative peer environment often comes with the risk of ostracism, hurtful jokes, and even violence.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Because of this, statistically the suicide rate amongst LGBT adolescents is up to four times higher than that of their heterosexual peers due to bullying and rejection from peers or family members.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] The final major aspect of identity formation is self-esteem.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Self-esteem is defined as one's thoughts and feelings about one's self-concept and identity.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Most theories on self-esteem state that there is a grand desire, across all genders and ages, to maintain, protect and enhance their self-esteem.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Contrary to popular belief, there is no empirical evidence for a significant drop in self-esteem over the course of adolescence.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] "Barometric self-esteem" fluctuates rapidly and can cause severe distress and anxiety, but baseline self-esteem remains highly stable across adolescence.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] The validity of global self-esteem scales has been questioned, and many suggest that more specific scales might reveal more about the adolescent experience.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Girls are most likely to enjoy high self-esteem when engaged in supportive relationships with friends, the most important function of friendship to them is having someone who can provide social and moral support.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Girls suffer from low self-esteem when they fail to win friends' approval or cannot find someone with whom to share common activities and common interests.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] In contrast, boys are more concerned with establishing and asserting their independence and defining their relation to authority.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Due to the fact that both men and women happen to have a low self-esteem after ending a romantic relationship, they are prone to other symptoms that is caused by this state.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Depression and hopelessness are only two of the various symptoms and it is said that women are twice as likely to experience depression and men are three to four times more likely to commit suicide.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] The relationships adolescents have with their peers, family, and members of their social sphere play a vital role in the social development of an adolescent.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] As an adolescent's social sphere develops rapidly as they distinguish the differences between friends and acquaintances, they often become heavily emotionally invested in friends.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] This is not harmful; however, if these friends expose an individual to potentially harmful situations, this is an aspect of peer pressure.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Adolescence is a critical period in social development because adolescents can be easily influenced by the people they develop close relationships with.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] This is the first time individuals can truly make their own decisions, which also makes this a sensitive period.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Relationships are vital in the social development of an adolescent due to the extreme influence peers can have over an individual.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] These relationships become significant because they begin to help the adolescent understand the concept of personalities, how they form, and why a person has that specific type of personality.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] "The use of psychological comparisons could serve both as an index of the growth of an implicit personality theory and as a component process accounting for its creation.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] In social comparison, we use reference groups, with respect to both psychological and identity development.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] These reference groups are the peers of adolescents.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] This means that who the teen chooses/accepts as their friends and who they communicate with on a frequent basis often makes up their reference groups and can therefore have a huge impact on who they become.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Research shows that relationships have the largest affect over the social development of an individual.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Adolescence marks a rapid change in one's role within a family.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Young children tend to assert themselves forcefully, but are unable to demonstrate much influence over family decisions until early adolescence, when they are increasingly viewed by parents as equals.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] The adolescent faces the task of increasing independence while preserving a caring relationship with their parents.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] When children go through puberty, there is often a significant increase in parent–child conflict and a less cohesive familial bond.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Arguments often concern minor issues of control, such as curfew, acceptable clothing, and the adolescent's right to privacy, which adolescents may have previously viewed as issues over which their parents had complete authority.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Parent–adolescent disagreement also increases as friends demonstrate a greater impact on one another, introducing new influences on the adolescent that may be in opposition to parents' values.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Social media has also played an increasing role in adolescent and parent disagreements.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] While parents never had to worry about the threats of social media in the past, it has become a dangerous place for children.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] While adolescents strive for their freedoms, the unknowns to parents of what their child is doing on social media sites is a challenging subject, due to the increasing amount of predators on social media sites.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Many parents have very little knowledge of social networking sites in the first place and this further increases their mistrust.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] An important challenge for the parent–adolescent relationship is to understand how to enhance the opportunities of online communication while managing its risks.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Although conflicts between children and parents increase during adolescence, these are just relatively minor issues.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Regarding their important life issues, most adolescents still share the same attitudes and values as their parents.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] During childhood, siblings are a source of conflict and frustration as well as a support system.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Adolescence may affect this relationship differently, depending on the sibling's gender.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] In same-sex sibling pairs, intimacy increases during early adolescence, then remains stable.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Mixed-sex siblings pairs act differently; siblings drift apart during early adolescent years, but experience an increase in intimacy starting at middle adolescence.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Sibling interactions are children's first relational experiences, the ones that shape their social and self-understanding for life.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Sustaining positive sibling relations can assist adolescents in a number of ways.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Siblings are able to act as peers, and may increase one another's sociability and feelings of self-worth.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Older siblings can give guidance to younger siblings, although the impact of this can be either positive or negative depending on the activity of the older sibling.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] A potential important influence on adolescence is change of the family dynamic, specifically divorce.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] With the divorce rate up to about 50%, divorce is common and adds to the already great amount of change in adolescence.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Custody disputes soon after a divorce often reflect a playing out of control battles and ambivalence between parents.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Divorce usually results in less contact between the adolescent and their noncustodial parent.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] In extreme cases of instability and abuse in homes, divorce can have a positive effect on families due to less conflict in the home.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] However, most research suggests a negative effect on adolescence as well as later development.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] A recent study found that, compared with peers who grow up in stable post-divorce families, children of divorce who experience additional family transitions during late adolescence make less progress in their math and social studies performance over time.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] A parental divorce during childhood or adolescence continues to have a negative effect when a person is in their twenties and early thirties.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] These negative effects include romantic relationships and conflict style, meaning that, as adults, they are more likely to use the styles of avoidance and competing in conflict management.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Despite changing family roles during adolescence, the home environment and parents are still important for the behaviors and choices of adolescents.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Adolescents who have a good relationship with their parents are less likely to engage in various risky behaviors, such as smoking, drinking, fighting, or unprotected sexual intercourse.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] In addition, parents influence the education of adolescence.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Students of a U.S. university do an outdoor class, where they discuss topics while walking.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Students study in a U.S. university library, using books and laptops.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Peer groups are essential to social and general development.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Communication with peers increases significantly during adolescence and peer relationships become more intense than in other stages and more influential to the teen, affecting both their decisions and choices.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] High-quality friendships may enhance children's development regardless of the characteristics of those friends.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] As children begin to bond with various people and create friendships, it later helps them when they are adolescent and sets up the framework for adolescence and peer groups.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Peer groups are especially important during adolescence, a period of development characterized by a dramatic increase in time spent with peers and a decrease in adult supervision.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Adolescents also associate with friends of the opposite sex much more than in childhood and tend to identify with larger groups of peers based on shared characteristics.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] It is also common for adolescents to use friends as coping devices in different situations.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] A three-factor structure of dealing with friends including avoidance, mastery, and nonchalance has shown that adolescents use friends as coping devices with social stresses.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Communication within peer groups allows adolescents to explore their feelings and identity as well as develop and evaluate their social skills.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Peer groups offer members the opportunity to develop social skills such as empathy, sharing, and leadership.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Adolescents choose peer groups based on characteristics similarly found in themselves.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] By utilizing these relationships, adolescents become more accepting of who they are becoming.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Group norms and values are incorporated into an adolescent's own self-concept.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Through developing new communication skills and reflecting upon those of their peers, as well as self-opinions and values, an adolescent can share and express emotions and other concerns without fear of rejection or judgment.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Peer groups can have positive influences on an individual, such as on academic motivation and performance.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] However, while peers may facilitate social development for one another, they may also hinder it.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Peers can have negative influences, such as encouraging experimentation with drugs, drinking, vandalism, and stealing through peer pressure.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Susceptibility to peer pressure increases during early adolescence, peaks around age 14, and declines thereafter.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Further evidence of peers hindering social development has been found in Spanish teenagers, where emotional (rather than solution-based) reactions to problems and emotional instability have been linked with physical aggression against peers.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Both physical and relational aggression are linked to a vast number of enduring psychological difficulties, especially depression, as is social rejection.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Because of this, bullied adolescents often develop problems that lead to further victimization.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Bullied adolescents are more likely to both continue to be bullied and to bully others in the future.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] However, this relationship is less stable in cases of cyberbullying, a relatively new issue among adolescents.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Adolescents tend to associate with "cliques" on a small scale and "crowds" on a larger scale.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] During early adolescence, adolescents often associate in cliques, exclusive, single-sex groups of peers with whom they are particularly close which may help adolescents become socially acclimated and form a stronger sense of identity.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Within a clique of highly athletic male peers, for example, the clique may create a stronger sense of fidelity and competition.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Cliques also have become somewhat a "collective parent", i.e. telling the adolescents what to do and not to do.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Towards late adolescence, cliques often merge into mixed-sex groups as teenagers begin romantically engaging with one another.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] These small friend groups then break down further as socialization becomes more couple-oriented.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] On a larger scale, adolescents often associate with *crowds*, groups of individuals who share a common interest or activity.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Often, crowd identities may be the basis for stereotyping young people, such as jocks or nerds.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] In large, multi-ethnic high schools, there are often ethnically determined crowds.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Adolescents use online technology to experiment with emerging identities and to broaden their peer groups, such as increasing the amount of friends acquired on Facebook and other social media sites.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Some adolescents use these newer channels to enhance relationships with peers however there can be negative uses as well such as cyberbullying, as mentioned previously, and negative impacts on the family.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Romantic relationships tend to increase in prevalence throughout adolescence.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] By age 15, 53% of adolescents have had a romantic relationship that lasted at least one month over the course of the previous 18 months.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] In a 2008 study conducted by YouGov for Channel 4, 20% of 14−17-year-olds surveyed revealed that they had their first sexual experience at 13 or under in the United Kingdom.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] A 2002 American study found that those aged 15–44 reported that the average age of first sexual intercourse was 17.0 for males and 17.3 for females.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] The typical duration of relationships increases throughout the teenage years as well.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Long-term relationships allow adolescents to gain the skills necessary for high-quality relationships later in life and develop feelings of self-worth.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Overall, positive romantic relationships among adolescents can result in long-term benefits.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] High-quality romantic relationships are associated with higher commitment in early adulthood and are positively associated with self-esteem, self-confidence, and social competence.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] For example, an adolescent with positive self-confidence is likely to consider themselves a more successful partner, whereas negative experiences may lead to low confidence as a romantic partner.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Adolescents often date within their demographic in regards to race, ethnicity, popularity, and physical attractiveness.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] However, there are traits in which certain individuals, particularly adolescent girls, seek diversity.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] While most adolescents date people approximately their own age, boys typically date partners the same age or younger; girls typically date partners the same age or older.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Some researchers are now focusing on learning about how adolescents view their own relationships and sexuality; they want to move away from a research point of view that focuses on the problems associated with adolescent sexuality.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] College Professor Lucia O'Sullivan and her colleagues found that there were no significant gender differences in the relationship events adolescent boys and girls from grades 7–12 reported.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Most teens said they had kissed their partners, held hands with them, thought of themselves as being a couple, and told people they were in a relationship.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] This means that private thoughts about the relationship as well as public recognition of the relationship were both important to the adolescents in the sample.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Sexual events (such as sexual touching and sexual intercourse) were less common than romantic events (holding hands) and social events (being with one's partner in a group setting).
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] The researchers state that these results are important because the results focus on the more positive aspects of adolescents and their social and romantic interactions rather than focusing on sexual behavior and its consequences.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Adolescence marks a time of sexual maturation, which manifests in social interactions as well.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] While adolescents may engage in casual sexual encounters (often referred to as hookups), most sexual experience during this period of development takes place within romantic relationships.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Adolescents can use technologies and social media to seek out romantic relationships, as they feel it is a safe place to try out dating and identity exploration.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] From these social media encounters, a further relationship may begin.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Among young adolescents, "heavy" sexual activity, marked by genital stimulation, is often associated with violence, depression, and poor relationship quality.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] This effect does not hold true for sexual activity in late adolescence that takes place within a romantic relationship.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Some research suggest that there are genetic causes of early sexual activity that are also risk factors for delinquency, suggesting that there is a group who are at risk for both early sexual activity and emotional distress.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] For older adolescents, though, sexual activity in the context of romantic relationships was actually correlated with lower levels of deviant behavior after controlling for genetic risks, as opposed to sex outside of a relationship (hook-ups).
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Dating violence can occur within adolescent relationships.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] When surveyed, 12–25% of adolescents reported having experienced physical violence in the context of a relationship while a quarter to a third of adolescents reported having experiencing psychological aggression.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] This reported aggression includes hitting, throwing things, or slaps, although most of this physical aggression does not result in a medical visit.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Physical aggression in relationships tends to decline from high school through college and young adulthood.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] In heterosexual couples, there is no significant difference between the rates of male and female aggressors, unlike in adult relationships.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Female adolescents from minority populations are at increased risk for intimate partner violence (IPV).
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Recent research findings suggest that a substantial portion of young urban females are at high risk for being victims of multiple forms of IPV.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Practitioners diagnosing depression among urban minority teens should assess for both physical and non-physical forms of IPV, and early detection can help to identify youths in need of intervention and care.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Similarly to adult victims, adolescent victims do not readily disclose abuse, and may seek out medical care for problems not directly related to incidences of IPV.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Therefore, screening should be a routine part of medical treatment for adolescents regardless of chief complaint.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Many adults discount instances of IPV in adolescents or believe they do not occur because relationships at young ages are viewed as "puppy love," however, it is crucial that adults take IPV in adolescents seriously even though often policy falls behind.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] In contemporary society, adolescents also face some risks as their sexuality begins to transform.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] One in four sexually active teenagers will contract an STI.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Adolescents in the United States often choose "anything but intercourse" for sexual activity because they mistakenly believe it reduces the risk of STIs.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Across the country, clinicians report rising diagnoses of herpes and human papillomavirus (HPV), which can cause genital warts, and is now thought to affect 15 percent of the teen population.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Girls 15 to 19 have higher rates of gonorrhea than any other age group.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] One-quarter of all new HIV cases occur in those under the age of 21.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Multrine also states in her article that according to a March survey by the Kaiser Family Foundation, eighty-one percent of parents want schools to discuss the use of condoms and contraception with their children.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] They also believe students should be able to be tested for STIs.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] Furthermore, teachers want to address such topics with their students.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] But, although 9 in 10 sex education instructors across the country believe that students should be taught about contraceptives in school, over one quarter report receiving explicit instructions from school boards and administrators not to do so.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p02] According to anthropologist Margaret Mead, the turmoil found in adolescence in Western society has a cultural rather than a physical cause; they reported that societies where young women engaged in free sexual activity had no such adolescent turmoil.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] There are certain characteristics of adolescent development that are more rooted in culture than in human biology or cognitive structures.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Culture has been defined as the "symbolic and behavioral inheritance received from the past that provides a community framework for what is valued".
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Culture is learned and socially shared, and it affects all aspects of an individual's life.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Social responsibilities, sexual expression, and belief system development, for instance, are all things that are likely to vary by culture.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Furthermore, distinguishing characteristics of youth, including dress, music and other uses of media, employment, art, food and beverage choices, recreation, and language, all constitute a youth culture.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] For these reasons, culture is a prevalent and powerful presence in the lives of adolescents, and therefore we cannot fully understand today's adolescents without studying and understanding their culture.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] However, "culture" should not be seen as synonymous with nation or ethnicity.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Many cultures are present within any given country and racial or socioeconomic group.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Furthermore, to avoid ethnocentrism, researchers must be careful not to define the culture's role in adolescence in terms of their own cultural beliefs.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] In his short book "The Teenage Consumer" published in July 1959, the British market research pioneer Mark Abrams identified the emergence of a new economic group of people aged 13–25.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Compared to children, people in this age range had more money, more discretion on how they chose to spend it, and greater mobility through the advent of the motor car.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Compared to adults, people in this age range had fewer responsibilities and therefore made different choices on how to spend their money.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] These unique characteristics of this new economic group presented challenges and opportunities to advertisers.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Mark Abrams coined the term "teenager" to describe this group of consumers aged 13–25.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] In Britain, teenagers first came to public attention during the Second World War, when there were fears of juvenile delinquency.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] By the 1950s, the media presented teenagers in terms of generational rebellion.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] The exaggerated moral panic among politicians and the older generation was typically belied by the growth in intergenerational cooperation between parents and children.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Many working-class parents, enjoying newfound economic security, eagerly took the opportunity to encourage their teens to enjoy more adventurous lives.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Schools were falsely portrayed as dangerous blackboard jungles under the control of rowdy kids.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] The media distortions of the teens as too affluent, and as promiscuous, delinquent, counter-cultural rebels do not reflect the actual experiences of ordinary young adults, particularly young women.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] The degree to which adolescents are perceived as autonomous beings varies widely by culture, as do the behaviors that represent this emerging autonomy.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Psychologists have identified three main types of autonomy: emotional independence, behavioral autonomy, and cognitive autonomy.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Emotional autonomy is defined in terms of an adolescent's relationships with others, and often includes the development of more mature emotional connections with adults and peers.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Behavioral autonomy encompasses an adolescent's developing ability to regulate their own behavior, to act on personal decisions, and to self-govern.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Cultural differences are especially visible in this category because it concerns issues of dating, social time with peers, and time-management decisions.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Cognitive autonomy describes the capacity for an adolescent to partake in processes of independent reasoning and decision-making without excessive reliance on social validation.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Converging influences from adolescent cognitive development, expanding social relationships, an increasingly adultlike appearance, and the acceptance of more rights and responsibilities enhance feelings of autonomy for adolescents.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Proper development of autonomy has been tied to good mental health, high self-esteem, self-motivated tendencies, positive self-concepts, and self-initiating and regulating behaviors.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Furthermore, it has been found that adolescents' mental health is best when their feelings about autonomy match closely with those of their parents.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] A questionnaire called the teen timetable has been used to measure the age at which individuals believe adolescents should be able to engage in behaviors associated with autonomy.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] This questionnaire has been used to gauge differences in cultural perceptions of adolescent autonomy, finding, for instance, that White parents and adolescents tend to expect autonomy earlier than those of Asian descent.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] It is, therefore, clear that cultural differences exist in perceptions of adolescent autonomy, and such differences have implications for the lifestyles and development of adolescents.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] In sub-Saharan African youth, the notions of individuality and freedom may not be useful in understanding adolescent development.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Rather, African notions of childhood and adolescent development are relational and interdependent.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] The lifestyle of an adolescent in a given culture is profoundly shaped by the roles and responsibilities he or she is expected to assume.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] The extent to which an adolescent is expected to share family responsibilities is one large determining factor in normative adolescent behavior.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] For instance, adolescents in certain cultures are expected to contribute significantly to household chores and responsibilities.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Household chores are frequently divided into self-care tasks and family-care tasks.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] However, specific household responsibilities for adolescents may vary by culture, family type, and adolescent age.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Some research has shown that adolescent participation in family work and routines has a positive influence on the development of an adolescent's feelings of self-worth, care, and concern for others.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] In addition to the sharing of household chores, certain cultures expect adolescents to share in their family's financial responsibilities.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] According to family economic and financial education specialists, adolescents develop sound money management skills through the practices of saving and spending money, as well as through planning ahead for future economic goals.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] For instance, in many developing countries it is common for children to attend fewer years of formal schooling so that, when they reach adolescence, they can begin working.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] While adolescence is a time frequently marked by participation in the workforce, the number of adolescents in the workforce is much lower now than in years past as a result of increased accessibility and perceived importance of formal higher education.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] For example, half of all 16-year-olds in China were employed in 1980, whereas less than one fourth of this same cohort were employed in 1990.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Furthermore, the amount of time adolescents spend on work and leisure activities varies greatly by culture as a result of cultural norms and expectations, as well as various socioeconomic factors.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] American teenagers spend less time in school or working and more time on leisure activities—which include playing sports, socializing, and caring for their appearance—than do adolescents in many other countries.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] These differences may be influenced by cultural values of education and the amount of responsibility adolescents are expected to assume in their family or community.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Time management, financial roles, and social responsibilities of adolescents are therefore closely connected with the education sector and processes of career development for adolescents, as well as to cultural norms and social expectations.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] In many ways, adolescents' experiences with their assumed social roles and responsibilities determine the length and quality of their initial pathway into adult roles.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Adolescence is frequently characterized by a transformation of an adolescent's understanding of the world, the rational direction towards a life course, and the active seeking of new ideas rather than the unquestioning acceptance of adult authority.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] An adolescent begins to develop a unique belief system through their interaction with social, familial, and cultural environments.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] While organized religion is not necessarily a part of every adolescent's life experience, youth are still held responsible for forming a set of beliefs about themselves, the world around them, and whatever higher powers they may or may not believe in.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] This process is often accompanied or aided by cultural traditions that intend to provide a meaningful transition to adulthood through a ceremony, ritual, confirmation, or rite of passage.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Many cultures define the transition into adultlike sexuality by specific biological or social milestones in an adolescent's life.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] For example, menarche (the first menstrual period of a female), or semenarche (the first ejaculation of a male) are frequent sexual defining points for many cultures.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] In addition to biological factors, an adolescent's sexual socialization is highly dependent upon whether their culture takes a restrictive or permissive attitude toward teen or premarital sexual activity.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] In the United States specifically, adolescents are said to have "raging hormones" that drive their sexual desires.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] These sexual desires are then dramatized regarding teen sex and seen as "a site of danger and risk; that such danger and risk is a source of profound worry among adults".
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] There is little to no normalization regarding teenagers having sex in the U.S., which causes conflict in how adolescents are taught about sex education.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] There is a constant debate about whether abstinence-only sex education or comprehensive sex education should be taught in schools and this stems back to whether or not the country it is being taught in is permissive or restrictive.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Restrictive cultures overtly discourage sexual activity in unmarried adolescents or until an adolescent undergoes a formal rite of passage.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] These cultures may attempt to restrict sexual activity by separating males and females throughout their development, or through public shaming and physical punishment when sexual activity does occur.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] In less restrictive cultures, there is more tolerance for displays of adolescent sexuality, or of the interaction between males and females in public and private spaces.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Less restrictive cultures may tolerate some aspects of adolescent sexuality, while objecting to other aspects.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] For instance, some cultures find teenage sexual activity acceptable but teenage pregnancy highly undesirable.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Other cultures do not object to teenage sexual activity or teenage pregnancy, as long as they occur after marriage.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] In permissive societies, overt sexual behavior among unmarried teens is perceived as acceptable, and is sometimes even encouraged.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Regardless of whether a culture is restrictive or permissive, there are likely to be discrepancies in how females versus males are expected to express their sexuality.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Cultures vary in how overt this double standard is—in some it is legally inscribed, while in others it is communicated through social convention.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Lesbian, gay, bisexual and transgender youth face much discrimination through bullying from those unlike them and may find telling others that they are gay to be a traumatic experience.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] The range of sexual attitudes that a culture embraces could thus be seen to affect the beliefs, lifestyles, and societal perceptions of its adolescents.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Adolescence is a period frequently marked by increased rights and privileges for individuals.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] While cultural variation exists for legal rights and their corresponding ages, considerable consistency is found across cultures.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Furthermore, since the advent of the Convention on the Rights of the Child in 1989 (children here defined as under 18), almost every country in the world (except the U.S. and South Sudan) has legally committed to advancing an anti-discriminatory stance towards young people of all ages.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] This includes protecting children against unchecked child labor, enrollment in the military, prostitution, and pornography.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] In many societies, those who reach a certain age (often 18, though this varies) are considered to have reached the age of majority and are legally regarded as adults who are responsible for their actions.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] People below this age are considered minors or children.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] A person below the age of majority may gain adult rights through legal emancipation.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] The legal working age in Western countries is usually 14 to 16, depending on the number of hours and type of employment under consideration.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Many countries also specify a minimum school leaving age, at which a person is legally allowed to leave compulsory education.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] This age varies greatly cross-culturally, spanning from 10 to 18, which further reflects the diverse ways formal education is viewed in cultures around the world.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] In most democratic countries, a citizen is eligible to vote at age 18.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] In a minority of countries, the voting age is as low as 16 (for example, Brazil), and at one time was as high as 25 in Uzbekistan.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] The age of consent to sexual activity varies widely between jurisdictions, ranging from 12 to 20 years, as does the age at which people are allowed to marry.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Specific legal ages for adolescents that also vary by culture are enlisting in the military, gambling, and the purchase of alcohol, cigarettes or items with parental advisory labels.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] The legal coming of age often does not correspond with the sudden realization of autonomy; many adolescents who have legally reached adult age are still dependent on their guardians or peers for emotional and financial support.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Nonetheless, new legal privileges converge with shifting social expectations to usher in a phase of heightened independence or social responsibility for most legal adolescents.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Following a steady decline beginning in the late 1990s up through the mid-2000s and a moderate increase in the early 2010s, illicit drug use among adolescents has roughly plateaued in the U.S.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Aside from alcohol, marijuana is the most commonly indulged drug habit during adolescent years.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Data collected by the National Institute on Drug Abuse shows that between the years of 2015 and 2018, past year marijuana usage among 8th graders declined from 11.8% to 10.5%; among 10th grade students, usage rose from 25.4% to 27.50%; and among 12th graders, usage rose slightly from 34.9% to 35.9%.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Additionally, while the early 2010s saw a surge in the popularity of MDMA, usage has stabilized with 2.2% of 12th graders using MDMA in the past year in the U.S.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] The heightened usage of ecstasy most likely ties in at least to some degree with the rising popularity of rave culture.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] One significant contribution to the increase in teenage substance abuse is an increase in the availability of prescription medication.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] With an increase in the diagnosis of behavioral and attentional disorders for students, taking pharmaceutical drugs such as Vicodin and Adderall for pleasure has become a prevalent activity among adolescents: 9.9% of high school seniors report having abused prescription drugs within the past year.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] In the U.S., teenage alcohol use rose in the late 2000s and is currently stable at a moderate level.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Out of a polled body of U.S. students age 12–18, 8.2% of 8th graders reported having been on at least one occasion having consumed alcohol within the previous month; for 10th graders, the number was 18.6%, and for 12th graders, 30.2%.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] More drastically, cigarette smoking has become a far less prevalent activity among American middle- and high-school students; in fact, a greater number of teens now smoke marijuana than smoke cigarettes, with one recent study showing a respective 23.8% versus 43.6% of surveyed high school seniors.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Recent studies have shown that male late adolescents are far more likely to smoke cigarettes rather than females.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] The study indicated that there was a discernible gender difference in the prevalence of smoking among the students.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] The finding of the study shows that more males than females began smoking when they were in primary and high schools whereas most females started smoking after high school.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] This may be attributed to recent changing social and political views towards marijuana; issues such as medicinal use and legalization have tended towards painting the drug in a more positive light than historically, while cigarettes continue to be vilified due to associated health risks.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Different drug habits often relate to one another in a highly significant manner.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] It has been demonstrated that adolescents who drink at least to some degree may be as much as sixteen times more likely than non-drinkers to use illicit drugs.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Peer acceptance and social norms gain a significantly greater hand in directing behavior at the onset of adolescence; as such, the alcohol and illegal drug habits of teens tend to be shaped largely by the substance use of friends and other classmates.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] In fact, studies suggest that more significantly than actual drug norms, an individual's perception of the illicit drug use by friends and peers is highly associated with their own habits in substance use during both middle and high school, a relationship that increases in strength over time.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Whereas social influences on alcohol use and marijuana use tend to work directly in the short term, peer and friend norms on smoking cigarettes in middle school have a profound effect on one's own likelihood to smoke cigarettes well into high school.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Perhaps the strong correlation between peer influence in middle school and cigarette smoking in high school may be explained by the addictive nature of cigarettes, which could lead many students to continue their smoking habits from middle school into late adolescence.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Until mid-to-late adolescence, boys and girls show relatively little difference in drinking motives.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Distinctions between the reasons for alcohol consumption of males and females begin to emerge around ages 14–15; overall, boys tend to view drinking in a more social light than girls, who report on average a more frequent use of alcohol as a coping mechanism.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] The latter effect appears to shift in late adolescence and onset of early adulthood (20–21 years of age); however, despite this trend, age tends to bring a greater desire to drink for pleasure rather than coping in both boys and girls.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Drinking habits and the motives behind them often reflect certain aspects of an individual's personality; in fact, four dimensions of the Five-Factor Model of personality demonstrate associations with drinking motives (all but 'Openness').
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Greater enhancement motives for alcohol consumption tend to reflect high levels of extraversion and sensation-seeking in individuals; such enjoyment motivation often also indicates low conscientiousness, manifesting in lowered inhibition and a greater tendency towards aggression.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] On the other hand, drinking to cope with negative emotional states correlates strongly with high neuroticism and low agreeableness.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Alcohol use as a negative emotion control mechanism often links with many other behavioral and emotional impairments, such as anxiety, depression, and low self-esteem.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Research has generally shown striking uniformity across different cultures in the motives behind teen alcohol use.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Social engagement and personal enjoyment appear to play a fairly universal role in adolescents' decision to drink throughout separate cultural contexts.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Surveys conducted in Argentina, Hong Kong, and Canada have each indicated the most common reason for drinking among adolescents to relate to pleasure and recreation; 80% of Argentinian teens reported drinking for enjoyment, while only 7% drank to improve a bad mood.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] The most prevalent answers among Canadian adolescents were to "get in a party mood," 18%; "because I enjoy it," 16%; and "to get drunk," 10%.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] In Hong Kong, female participants most frequently reported drinking for social enjoyment, while males most frequently reported drinking to feel the effects of alcohol.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Much research has been conducted on the psychological ramifications of body image on adolescents.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Modern day teenagers are exposed to more media on a daily basis than any generation before them.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] As such, modern day adolescents are exposed to many representations of ideal, societal beauty.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] The concept of a person being unhappy with their own image or appearance has been defined as "body dissatisfaction".
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] In teenagers, body dissatisfaction is often associated with body mass, low self-esteem, and atypical eating patterns that can result in health procedures.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Scholars continue to debate the effects of media on body dissatisfaction in teens.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Because exposure to media has increased over the past decade, adolescents' use of computers, cell phones, stereos and televisions to gain access to various mediums of popular culture has also increased.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Almost all American households have at least one television, more than three-quarters of all adolescents' homes have access to the Internet, and more than 90% of American adolescents use the Internet at least occasionally.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] As a result of the amount of time adolescents spend using these devices, their total media exposure is high.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] From 1996 to 2006, the amount of time that adolescents spent on the computer greatly increased.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Online activities with the highest rates of use among adolescents are video games (78% of adolescents), email (73%), instant messaging (68%), social networking sites (65%), news sources (63%), music (59%), and videos (57%).
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] In the 2000s, social networking sites proliferated and a high proportion of adolescents used them.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] As of 2012, 73% of 12–17 year olds reported having at least one social networking profile; two-thirds (68%) of teens texted every day, half (51%) visited social networking sites daily, and 11% sent or received tweets at least once every day.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] More than a third (34%) of teens visited their main social networking site several times a day.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] One in four (23%) teens were "heavy" social media users, meaning they used at least two different types of social media each and every day.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Although research has been inconclusive, some findings have indicated that electronic communication negatively affects adolescents' social development, replaces face-to-face communication, impairs their social skills, and can sometimes lead to unsafe interaction with strangers.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Studies have shown differences in the ways the internet negatively impacts adolescents' social functioning.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Online socializing tends to make girls particularly vulnerable, while socializing in Internet cafés seems only to affect boys' academic achievement.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] However, other research suggests that Internet communication brings friends closer and is beneficial for socially anxious teens, who find it easier to interact socially online.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] A broad way of defining adolescence is the transition from child-to-adulthood.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] According to Hogan & Astone (1986), this transition can include markers such as leaving school, starting a full-time job, leaving the home of origin, getting married, and becoming a parent for the first time.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] However, the time frame of this transition varies drastically by culture.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] In some countries, such as the United States, adolescence can last nearly a decade, but in others, the transition—often in the form of a ceremony—can last for only a few days.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Some examples of social and religious transition ceremonies that can be found in the U.S., as well as in other cultures around the world, are Confirmation, Bar and Bat Mitzvahs, Quinceañeras, sweet sixteens, cotillions, and débutante balls.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] In other countries, initiation ceremonies play an important role, marking the transition into adulthood or the entrance into adolescence.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] This transition may be accompanied by obvious physical changes, which can vary from a change in clothing to tattoos and scarification.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Furthermore, transitions into adulthood may also vary by gender, and specific rituals may be more common for males or for females.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] This illuminates the extent to which adolescence is, at least in part, a social construction; it takes shape differently depending on the cultural context, and may be enforced more by cultural practices or transitions than by universal chemical or biological physical changes.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] At the decision-making point of their lives, youth are susceptible to drug addiction, sexual abuse, peer pressure, violent crimes and other illegal activities.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Developmental Intervention Science (DIS) is a fusion of the literature of both developmental and intervention sciences.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] This association conducts youth interventions that mutually assist both the needs of the community as well as psychologically stranded youth by focusing on risky and inappropriate behaviors while promoting positive self-development along with self-esteem among adolescents.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] The concept of adolescence has been criticized by experts, such as Robert Epstein, who state that an undeveloped brain is not the main cause of teenagers' turmoils.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Some have criticized the concept of adolescence because it is a relatively recent phenomenon in human history created by modern society, and have been highly critical of what they view as the infantilization of young adults in American society.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] In an article for *Scientific American*, Robert Epstein and Jennifer Ong state that "American-style teen turmoil is absent in more than 100 cultures around the world, suggesting that such mayhem is not biologically inevitable.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] Other critics of the concept of adolescence point at individual differences in brain growth rate, citing that some (though not all) early teens still have infantile undeveloped corpus callosums, concluding that "the adult in *every* adolescent" is too generalizing.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] They argue that this threshold is the one at which an individual is objectively capable of speaking for himself or herself, as opposed to culturally arbitrary measures of "maturity" which often treat this ability as a sign of "immaturity" merely because it leads to questioning of authorities.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] These people also stress the low probability of the threshold being reached at a birthday, and instead advocate non-chronological emancipation at the threshold of afterward correction of assumptions.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] In this context, they refer to the fallibility of official assumptions about what is good or bad for an individual, concluding that paternalistic "rights" may harm the individual.
[src:children-s-hospital/adolescents-p03] They also argue that since it never took many years to move from one group to another to avoid inbreeding in the Paleolithic, evolutionary psychology is unable to account for a long period of "immature" risk behavior.
[src:children-s-hospital/agency-for-healthcare-research-and-quality] The **Agency for Healthcare Research and Quality** (**AHRQ**; pronounced "ark" by initiates and often "A-H-R-Q" by the public) is one of twelve agencies within the United States Department of Health and Human Services (HHS).
[src:children-s-hospital/agency-for-healthcare-research-and-quality] The agency is headquartered in North Bethesda, Maryland, a suburb of Washington, D.C.
[src:children-s-hospital/agency-for-healthcare-research-and-quality] As part of the announced 2025 HHS reorganization, AHRQ is planned to be integrated into the new HHS Office of Strategy.
[src:children-s-hospital/agency-for-healthcare-research-and-quality] AHRQ's earliest predecessor was the **National Center for Health Services Research and Development**, established in 1968 within the short-lived PHS Health Services and Mental Health Administration (HSMHA) during the 1966–1973 PHS reorganizations.
[src:children-s-hospital/agency-for-healthcare-research-and-quality] It was established largely through the efforts of members of the NIH Division of Research Grants Health Services Study Section.
[src:children-s-hospital/agency-for-healthcare-research-and-quality] The new center quickly absorbed the PHS Division of Chronic Diseases, which dated back to 1949, in order to access the latter's larger budget.
[src:children-s-hospital/agency-for-healthcare-research-and-quality] When HSMHA was split up in 1973, the center was included in one of its successors, the Health Resources Administration.
[src:children-s-hospital/agency-for-healthcare-research-and-quality] It was renamed the **Bureau of Health Services Research** that year, and then the **National Center for Health Services Research** in 1975.
[src:children-s-hospital/agency-for-healthcare-research-and-quality] In 1978 it was transferred to the Office of the Assistant Secretary for Health.
[src:children-s-hospital/agency-for-healthcare-research-and-quality] In 1985 it was renamed the **National Center for Health Services Research and Health Care Technology Assessment**.
[src:children-s-hospital/agency-for-healthcare-research-and-quality] In 1989, the agency became its own operating agency within PHS, and was renamed **Agency for Health Care Policy and Research** (AHCPR) by the Omnibus Budget Reconciliation Act of 1989 (103 Stat.
[src:children-s-hospital/agency-for-healthcare-research-and-quality] However, AHCPR became controversial when it produced several guidelines that some thought would reduce medical drugs and procedures.
[src:children-s-hospital/agency-for-healthcare-research-and-quality] This included concern from ophthalmologists on a cataract guideline and concern by the pharmaceutical industry over a reduction in the use of new drugs.
[src:children-s-hospital/agency-for-healthcare-research-and-quality] AHCPR was reauthorized December 6, 1999, as the Agency for Healthcare Research and Quality (AHRQ) under the Healthcare Research and Quality Act of 1999, which amended Title IX of the Public Health Service Act (42 U.S.C.
[src:children-s-hospital/agency-for-healthcare-research-and-quality] The 2015 budget for AHRQ was US$440 million, $24 million less than FY 2014.
[src:children-s-hospital/agency-for-healthcare-research-and-quality] The budget includes $334 million in Public Health Service (PHS) Evaluation Funds, a decrease of $30 million from FY 2014, and $106 million from the Patient-Centered Outcomes Research Trust Fund, an increase of $13 million above FY 2014.
[src:children-s-hospital/agency-for-healthcare-research-and-quality] The FY 2015 budget is intended to ensure the Agency continues its progress on health services research to improve outcomes, affordability, and quality.
[src:children-s-hospital/agency-for-healthcare-research-and-quality] The budget also supports the collection of information on health care spending and use through the Healthcare Cost and Utilization Project (HCUP) and Medical Expenditure Panel Survey (MEPS).
[src:children-s-hospital/agency-for-healthcare-research-and-quality] In July 2018, the National Guideline Clearinghouse (NGC) and the National Quality Measures Clearinghouse (NQMC), two longtime online resources from the AHRQ, were shut down because federal funding ceased to be available to them.
[src:children-s-hospital/agency-for-healthcare-research-and-quality] Other stakeholders were exploring options for hosting the NGC ]; should that happen, it will return to the web.
[src:children-s-hospital/agency-for-healthcare-research-and-quality] On a continuing resolution, AHRQ’s fiscal year 2025 operating budget is $487 million, the same as fiscal year 2024.
[src:children-s-hospital/agency-for-healthcare-research-and-quality] The Office of Communications was previously known as the Office of Communications and Knowledge Transfer.
[src:children-s-hospital/agency-for-healthcare-research-and-quality] With this program, AHRQ serves as a "science partner" with private and public organizations in their efforts to improve the quality, effectiveness, and appropriateness of health care by synthesizing the evidence and facilitating the translation of evidence-based research findings.
[src:children-s-hospital/agency-for-healthcare-research-and-quality] Topics are nominated by Federal and non-Federal partners such as professional societies, health plans, insurers, employers, and patient groups.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] An **almshouse** is a form of charitable housing that developed in medieval Europe to provide long-term accommodation for people unable to support themselves, most often the elderly or disabled.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Originating from earlier hospital foundations associated with Christian charity, almshouses emerged as distinct institutions by the later medieval period, typically housing small numbers of residents rather than the larger, more transient populations found in hospitals.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Although found across Europe, their development is most fully documented in England, where they formed part of a wider system of poor relief alongside other charitable and parish-based support.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] From the late medieval period, almshouses were established by a wide variety of founders, including clergy, landowners, merchants, and civic groups, and were supported through endowments, donations, and oversight by trustees and local authorities.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Their design and role changed over time, particularly after the Reformation and the introduction of poor relief laws, but they continued to provide housing and limited support to their residents.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Although they served relatively small numbers throughout their history, almshouses remained an important part of charitable support and remain in use in the United Kingdom today.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] The term almshouse refers to charitable housing provided for people in need, especially the poor.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] In the medieval period, such institutions were more often called hospitals, using the older meaning of hospitality.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] The word almshouse was not used until the 14th century.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Medieval records use many different names for these institutions, including hospitals, Maison Dieu, bede-houses, lazar houses, and Godshouses.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] These terms were often used loosely, and the same institutions could be described in different ways.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Some provided care, some offered housing, and many did both.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] The word almshouse is also used to distinguish these institutions from workhouses, which were established in the late 17th century as parish-run buildings for the poor and were funded by local taxes.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] The term poorhouse is sometimes used for institutions housing the poor, but it more commonly refers to later, publicly funded institutions, especially in North America and Scotland, which differed in purpose and organization from almshouses.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] The development of almshouses is most fully documented in England.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Institutional care for the poor in Europe grew out of early Christian charity, including hospitals that appeared in the Byzantine Empire in the fourth century.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] In Western Europe, these developed into a range of charitable institutions, from which almshouses later emerged as a distinct form of housing for the poor.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Early foundations often took the form of houses of hospitality, offering shelter and basic support to travellers as well as to the sick, infirm, and elderly, and became common in both cities and smaller towns.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] In England, some of the earliest recorded hospitals date from before the Norman Conquest.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] In the medieval period, hospitals were places of hospitality, providing shelter and basic care rather than medical treatment alone.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Almshouses developed from these earlier hospital foundations and were closely connected to both royal and religious authority.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Their foundation often required formal approval through licences or charters, particularly when land was granted to provide a permanent income.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Many almshouses were supervised by the Church and linked with chantries and devotional practices.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Over time, almshouses developed as more specialized institutions, intended for smaller numbers of permanent residents, most often the elderly and infirm.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Hospitals and almshouses formed part of wider systems of poor relief, but served different roles.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Hospitals provided accommodation, care, and spiritual services to a broad range of people—including the sick, poor, and travellers—while almshouses were typically intended for a settled group of residents.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] From the 12th and 13th centuries, some almshouses were founded as permanent homes, while others developed from temporary shelters into long-term residences.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] In the later medieval era, almshouses became more common, typically housing fewer residents than hospitals and focusing on long-term accommodation rather than care.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] As leprosy declined, some former leprosy hospitals were adapted for use as almshouses or other forms of charitable housing.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] From the later 14th century, almshouses were increasingly founded by lay benefactors and typically managed by trustees.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Institutions specifically for the elderly remained relatively uncommon until the mid-15th century.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] By this time, the number of almshouses had increased, and the institution had emerged in a more recognizable form, providing accommodation for older people who had fallen into poverty.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] This pattern continued into the early modern period, with a marked increase in new foundations between about 1550 and 1650, particularly in towns, reflecting changing approaches to charity and poor relief.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Most medieval hospitals in England were closely linked to the Church and often connected to monasteries, convents or other religious institutions.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Many were named after saints, showing their religious character.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] In one study, most hospitals founded before 1350 had religious names, but this declined after 1350 as more were named after founders, places, or other features.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] The chantry system also shaped charitable foundations.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Some almshouses were set up as “bede-houses,” where residents were expected to pray for the souls of the founder and their family.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Not all almshouses were connected to the Church.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Some were founded locally by landowners to support tenants, servants, or neighbors, while others were created for specific groups, such as the homeless, Jews, poor clergy, struggling gentry, or women and children.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Almshouses grew out of earlier hospital foundations, but the difference between the two was often unclear.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Hospitals cared for a broad range of people, including the sick, the poor, and travellers, and usually provided food, shelter, and spiritual support, while almshouses served a narrower group, most often older or disabled people.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Unlike hospitals, almshouses mainly provided housing rather than active care.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Residents in almshouses were often expected to provide for themselves, although they might receive small payments or basic supplies such as food or fuel.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Many were admitted for life, as long as they followed the rules of the house.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Almshouses were generally smaller and less expensive than hospitals, and were more often named for their founders or location.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Hospitals, by contrast, tended to be larger, supporting more residents on average.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] In practice, the boundary between hospitals and almshouses was flexible.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Some institutions changed their role over time, and buildings originally founded for one purpose, such as leper hospitals, were later used to house other groups in need.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Almshouses were founded by people from a wide range of backgrounds, including tradesmen, clergy, merchants, gentry, and wealthy landowners.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] The wealth and status of both the founders and the institutions they created varied considerably.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Establishing an almshouse required substantial resources, and many founders had significant disposable wealth.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Although most were men, women also played an important role, acting as founders, co-founders, or executors of family estates, and increasingly establishing foundations in memory of deceased relatives.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Almshouses operated through charitable donations, and were closely linked to royal and Church authority.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Trade associations also established almshouses for aged or disabled members, including foundations by livery companies, leather sellers, tanners, clockmakers, drapers, and goldsmiths.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Providing for the poor was a shared Christian duty for both Catholics and Protestants, and for many founders it was sufficient motivation.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] For others, founding and supporting almshouses expressed their social role and values.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Among landowners in particular, caring for elderly tenants and local poor people was seen as a sign of status and moral responsibility, and almshouses could also serve as a way to be remembered.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Establishing an almshouse required a significant financial commitment, including creating a trust and providing a building.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Almshouses were supported through a range of sources, including donations, bequests, contributions from parishioners, and, in some cases, income from fairs.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Gifts were often left in wills, and charitable giving was encouraged by the Church.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Some institutions were also maintained, at least in part, by towns or parishes.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Many almshouses raised funds through organized collection, known as “gathering.” Individuals, commonly known as proctors or procurators, were appointed to solicit alms locally or across wider regions, sometimes traveling throughout the country.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] These collectors were expected to carry written authorization and could be appointed by the master, warden, or patrons of the institution.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] By the later 16th century, authorized alms-seeking had become more common, but fraud was a growing problem.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Permits could be altered or used by unauthorized individuals, and abuses became widespread.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Concerns over dishonesty contributed to the abolition of traditional forms of gathering under the Poor Laws of 1598 and 1601.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] The founder of an almshouse determined how it was to be governed, often appointing a master, warden, or keeper to manage it.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Before 1350, most houses were overseen by religious institutions.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Some were founded by monasteries or convents, while others were established by benefactors who placed them under religious supervision, and a few were self-governing.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] After 1350, more almshouses came under non-religious control, including management by parishes, guilds, schools, and urban authorities.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] By the early 16th century, many were supervised by parish officials such as churchwardens.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Each foundation was typically incorporated as a separate body, governed by a warden, with its own seal and the authority to make rules.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Later foundations, especially after the Reformation, were more commonly administered by trustees or civic bodies connected to local systems of poor relief.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] The physical layout of almshouses varied over time, reflecting changes in design and use.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] The 19th-century antiquarian and architect F.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Dollman described four main building types linked to medieval almshouses and related hospital foundations: infirmary halls without chapels; infirmary halls with attached chapels, cruciform layouts; and courtyard plans.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Most medieval almshouses were small, typically housing between four and thirteen residents.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Almshouses developed from monastic infirmaries, typically arranged as large halls with bed spaces along the walls and were connected to a chapel and, in some cases, a kitchen.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] These arrangements offered residents little privacy.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Similar hall-and-chapel designs were also found elsewhere in Europe, as at the Hospital Of St John in Bruge.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] From the later medieval period, courtyard designs became more common, with individual living spaces arranged around a central courtyard, often entered through a gate or archway, and with a residence for the master incorporated into the gatehouse.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] From the later 15th century, almshouses increasingly moved away from communal layouts toward individual living.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Residents were housed in separate rooms or small cottages, typically with one or two rooms and their own fireplace for heating and cooking.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] By the late 16th century, almshouses were commonly built as rows of cottages, usually located in the center of a village or town, near the parish church.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] This became the most common form in England.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] These buildings generally lacked chapels, communal areas, or accommodation for the master or warden, and often included small gardens for residents.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Similar arrangements were found in the Dutch Republic, and smaller almshouses might take the form of a single house divided into separate living quarters.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] In the 19th century, almshouses were typically built in small groups of between five and twelve dwellings, usually single-storey and modest in design, and were found in towns and villages across England.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Most surviving almshouses reflect this vernacular cottage form, shaped by local building traditions and materials, and some were adapted from existing private houses.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] More generous foundations sometimes included architectural features such as gatehouses, porches, or enclosed courtyards, and in a few cases retained a chapel for worship.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Separate and more comfortable accommodation was often provided for the master or warden.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Rules set by founders or trustees governed admission, selection, and the support provided.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] The most common requirement was that residents lived in the immediate neighborhood or parish.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Applicants were often expected to be elderly (though rarely a fixed age), as well as ill or incapacitated, and some houses excluded those considered disorderly, such as fighters, gamblers, beggars, or brawlers.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] The lame and the blind were an important group, and often given priority.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Some almshouses required an entry payment or expected residents to supply basic personal items such as clothing or bedding, indicating that they were not always destitute.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Living arrangements varied: some houses admitted single men, single women, married couples, or families, while others restricted residents to individuals, sometimes requiring older children to be placed in service.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Most information about almshouse residents comes from institutional records, as few first-person accounts survive from before 1800.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] From the 15th century onward, residents were typically elderly or disabled people who had previously supported themselves but had fallen into need through illness, injury, or old age.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Although many residents were poor, others had small incomes, particularly in institutions that required entrance payments.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Some urban almshouses also housed children temporarily before placing them in service or apprenticeships.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] By the later medieval period, almshouses were intended primarily for residents rather than clergy, and commonly housed both single individuals and married couples.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Some institutions were founded for specific groups, such as former servants, elderly sailors or soldiers, widows of clergy, or members of particular households.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] After 1540, many almshouses focused more narrowly on needy people unable to work, with preference often given to those affected by illness, military service, or sudden loss of property.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Although almshouses supported relatively small numbers, they played a limited but important role within wider systems of poor relief.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] After the Black Death, when the population was lower, informal charity was often able to meet the needs of many people facing hardship.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Daily life differed by foundation, but most residents received support in cash or in kind, including regular payments, fuel such as firewood, and occasional clothing allowances.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Food was sometimes provided in a shared hall or distributed to individuals, and residents were often referred to as “brothers” and “sisters”.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Early almshouses were typically communal, with residents sleeping in shared dormitories and eating in a common hall.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Over time, separate accommodation became more common, and men and women often lived and dined separately, reflecting the growing number of female residents.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] In some houses, residents were expected to provide their own food from personal resources, supplemented by basic allowances, while others required communal cooking and dining.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] At St Bartholomew's Hospital in Sandwich, Kent, for example, residents cooked together in a shared kitchen, contributing their own food to a common pot prepared by a cook.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] They also shared bread, cheese, and butter, and were permitted a jug of ale on Sundays.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Some almshouses required residents to wear distinctive clothing, such as the red cloaks and bonnets for women and blue coats and hats for men at St Johns' House in Sherborne in Dorset.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Some almshouses had formal rules for their residents, though many did not.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Where they did, they typically required attendance at church and prayer, especially in houses with chapels or chantry functions.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] They also expected residents to live peaceably, cleanly, and morally, avoiding swearing, drunkenness, gambling, taverns, and sexual misconduct.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Residents were required to keep their rooms and shared spaces clean, carry out basic chores, and limit time away from the house.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Discipline was usually overseen by a master or warden, often a clergyman, though in houses without regular supervision it fell to parish officials.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Penalties for misconduct could include fines, loss of allowances, or expulsion, but rules were not always strictly enforced, and removal could be difficult once a resident had been admitted.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] During the early stages of the English Reformation in the 1530s and 1540s, the dissolution of the monasteries (1536–1539), followed by the abolition of chantries (1545–1547) and the suppression of religious guilds (1548), had a major impact on almshouses and other forms of support for the poor.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Many almshouses were closely tied to these institutions, either as chantries or through monastic support, and their suppression led to widespread closure, reduction, or transfer to secular control, often with the loss of their endowments.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Estimates suggest that over 500 almshouses existed before the Reformation, but their number fell by about half by the mid-16th century, with roughly 260 hospitals and endowed almshouses closed between 1536 and 1549.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] The decline of these religious foundations reduced traditional forms of relief and contributed to growing concern about poverty, prompting new approaches to poor relief later in the 16th century.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] In the years following the Dissolution, few almshouses were established for more than 30 years.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] In the longer term, almshouse foundations became more widely distributed, with new houses established in villages and small towns as well as in the cathedral cities and former monastic centres where they had previously been concentrated.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Following the Dissolution of the Monasteries, the number of almshouses and hospitals declined sharply as many religious foundations were closed.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Those that remained, and those established after 1540, differed from their medieval predecessors in several ways: they were generally smaller, supported fewer people, and were more often intended for the elderly poor, particularly women, at a time of rapid population growth.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Some earlier houses survived, especially smaller or locally supported institutions, and were sometimes reorganized under new governance.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] At Lambourn, for example, the chantry chapel attached to Estbury’s almshouse was dissolved in 1547, but the almshouse continued and was re-established under trustees in 1589.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] From the later 16th century, more almshouses were founded in towns and cities by guilds, civic groups, and private benefactors.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Post-Reformation almshouses were less closely tied to religious institutions.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] While religious observance remained important, many no longer maintained chapels or resident clergy, and residents typically attended services in the parish church.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Their purpose shifted increasingly toward providing housing and support for the aged and disabled in line with new public poor relief laws, including the Elizabethan Poor Law of 1601.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Smaller charitable foundations without permanent endowments, along with parish and church housing, were likely more widespread than surviving records suggest and may have made a significant contribution to poor relief in early modern England.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] In the later 16th century, almshouse foundations increased, particularly for the elderly and disabled.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] From about 1550 to 1650, new houses were established in increasing numbers in response to population growth and rising poverty.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Many towns founded at least one almshouse during this period, though they were less common in rural parishes.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Post-Reformation almshouses differed in several respects from earlier foundations.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] They placed greater emphasis on individual living, with most residents provided their own rooms with fireplaces for cooking and heating.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Communal dining became less common, and some institutions included gardens for individual use.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Their religious identity was generally weaker, and practices such as begging were sometimes prohibited, with residents instead expected to work if able.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Almshouses for women became more common, and in mixed institutions women often outnumbered men, though they typically remained subordinate within the household structure.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] The Elizabethan era brought major changes in poor relief and charity, including the Poor Laws of 1598 and 1601.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] These laws reshaped how almshouses operated.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] They ended practices such as licensed begging and made it easier to found and support new institutions, helping to sustain almshouses and other forms of charity in later periods.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] The changes were less helpful for existing almshouses without adequate endowments.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] The abolition of licensed alms-gathering removed an important source of income, only partly replaced by local funds.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] As a result, many houses came under new forms of management, including charitable trusts, urban authorities, merchant companies, and parish oversight.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Responsibility for poor relief also shifted to the parish, which raised funds through local taxes and provided support, including housing, for those unable to support themselves.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] This expanded local provision but did not replace almshouses, which continued to operate alongside parish relief.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] By 1660, there were an estimated 1,000 almshouses in England, but parish-based poor relief had become the main system of support.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Workhouses, introduced from the late 17th century, were parish-run institutions funded by local taxes to house the poor.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Unlike almshouses, which were selective and supported by endowments, workhouses were part of the poor relief system and usually could not refuse those who qualified for support.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] During the 17th and 18th centuries, spending on poor relief increased and attitudes toward poverty shifted, with greater emphasis on work and discipline.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Measures such as the requirement for recipients to wear badges, introduced in 1697, reflected these views.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] The Workhouse Test Act of 1723 encouraged parishes to establish workhouses as the preferred form of relief.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] In practice, however, most poor people continued to receive support within the community.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Almshouses in this period were most often found in older towns, including cathedral towns and places that had grown significantly in the 16th and 17th centuries, when founding almshouses was a common form of philanthropy.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] After 1730, new almshouse foundations declined, and some existing houses fell into neglect, as workhouses were increasingly favored as a more economical way to support larger numbers of people.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] In the 19th century, particularly during the Victorian period, the building of almshouses increased after a long period of decline.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Many surviving almshouses date from the Victorian period, with estimates suggesting that more than 30% were built at this time.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Rapid industrial growth and the expansion of towns drew attention to the living conditions of poorer populations.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] At the same time, dissatisfaction with the workhouse system introduced under the Poor Law Amendment Act of 1834 led some donors to support other forms of assistance.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] New almshouses were founded by local benefactors, including industrialists and merchants.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] They were usually built as rows or groups of separate dwellings rather than large shared institutions, and often designed in decorative historic styles, such as Gothic Revival or Tudor Revival.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] They were generally intended for older people with limited income who were considered deserving of support.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Almshouses were established across Western Europe during the medieval period, often linked to hospitals, confraternities, or other charitable foundations.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] In some regions, including France and the Low Countries, they provided long-term accommodation for the poor and elderly, while others functioned more like hospitals or hospices.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Almshouses were found in both cities and smaller towns, where they offered basic support and lodging for the poor.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] They were typically smaller than urban hospitals and operated under a less formal religious organization, although both provided long-term care and essential support.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] In France and other parts of Western Europe, poor relief increasingly came under the control of urban authorities from the late medieval period onward.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Municipal governments used institutions such as hospitals to house and support the poor, reflecting a broader shift toward organized, civic charity.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Distinctions between the “deserving” and “undeserving” poor became increasingly important, and relief was often directed toward local residents rather than outsiders.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] The system of poor relief in the Netherlands (then the Dutch Republic) differed from that of England.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] While the English system was based on laws passed by Parliament and funded through local taxation, welfare in the Dutch Republic relied primarily on private and voluntary donations.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Almshouses formed one part of a wider range of institutions for the poor.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] English almshouses and Dutch *hofjes* were not the same, reflecting these differences in organization and funding, but their development followed similar patterns.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] In both England and the Netherlands, almshouses developed in part from medieval hospitals associated with religious foundations and, by the later medieval period, evolved into institutions providing housing for elderly people who had fallen into poverty through age or illness.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] In medieval and early modern Scotland, hospitals and almshouses primarily supported the poor rather than providing medical treatment.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] They provided housing and basic care for people affected by poverty, age, and illness.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Because Scotland had fewer large towns than many areas of Western Europe, care was provided through many small, local institutions rather than a few large hospitals, and some continued to operate after the Reformation.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Archaeological evidence suggests that around 170 of these institutions existed in medieval Scotland.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] In the United States, “almshouse” referred to institutions that differed from their medieval European counterparts, as there were very few private charitable endowments or religious welfare organizations in North America.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] While early almshouses were influenced by English charitable traditions, they developed into publicly funded institutions under local government control.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Commonly known as poorhouses, they housed a wide range of dependent populations, including the elderly, disabled, unemployed, children and the mentally ill.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Systems of poor relief in Canada developed differently under French and British colonial rule.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] In colonial New France, charitable assistance was organized largely through Catholic religious orders, supported in part by the French colonial government.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] These institutions provided care for the poor, elderly, and sick, and differed from the almshouse and poorhouse systems that later developed in English North America.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] In British North America, systems of poor relief varied widely by colony.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Some colonies, such as Nova Scotia and New Brunswick, adopted legislation influenced by the English Poor Laws, placing responsibility on local communities, while others relied more on informal support through families, churches, and voluntary charity.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] As a result, institutional care for the poor developed unevenly, and in some areas remained limited or absent.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Almshouses continue in use in the United Kingdom as a small form of charitable housing.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] About 1,600 independent charities provide accommodation for approximately 36,000 residents.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] They are run by trustees and regulated as charities, with admission often based on age, financial circumstances, and local or work connections.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Funding comes from a mix of historic endowments, investments, and donations.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Residents usually pay a small weekly sum, but do not hold standard tenancies, instead occupying their homes as beneficiaries of the charity.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Although many historic buildings have been updated, almshouses remain as independent, low-cost housing, primarily for older people with limited financial resources.
[src:children-s-hospital/almshouse] Examples still in use include St Mary’s Hospital Almshouses, Ewelme Almshouses, Drapers’ Almshouses, and Blythe Cottages.
[src:children-s-hospital/american-board-of-pediatrics] The **American Board of Pediatrics** (**ABP**) was founded in 1933.
[src:children-s-hospital/american-board-of-pediatrics] It is one of the 24 certifying boards of the American Board of Medical Specialties (ABMS).
[src:children-s-hospital/american-board-of-pediatrics] The ABP is an independent and nonprofit organization.
[src:children-s-hospital/american-board-of-pediatrics] The ABP's mission is to advance child health by certifying pediatricians who meet standards of excellence and are committed to continuous learning and improvement.
[src:children-s-hospital/american-board-of-pediatrics] The American Board of Pediatrics also awards certificates in conjunction with other specialty boards.
[src:children-s-hospital/american-board-of-pediatrics] Additionally, from 2001-2007, the ABP awarded certificates in Neurodevelopmental Disabilities.
[src:children-s-hospital/american-board-of-pediatrics] In 1933, the American Pediatric Society, the American Academy of Pediatrics, and the American Medical Association formed the American Board of Pediatrics for the purpose of examining and awarding certification to physicians who have superior knowledge in the field of the diseases of childhood.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] Asclepius was said to have been such a skilled doctor that he could even raise people from the dead.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] Stemming from the myth of his great healing powers, pilgrims would flock to temples built in his honor in order to seek spiritual and physical healing.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] Asclepieia included carefully controlled spaces conducive to healing and fulfilled several of the requirements of institutions created for healing.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] Treatment at these temples largely centered around promoting healthy lifestyles, with a particular emphasis on a person's spiritual needs.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] Characteristic of the Asclepieion was the practice of *incubatio*, also known as 'temple sleep.' This was a process by which patients would go to sleep in the temple with the expectation that they would be visited by Asclepius himself or one of his healing children in their dream.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] During this time, they would be told what it is that they needed to do in order to cure their ailment.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] At the very least, they would wake up having not been directly visited by a deity and instead report their dream to a priest.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] The priest would then interpret the dream and prescribe a cure, often a visit to the baths or a gymnasium.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] The preliminary treatment for admission into the Asclepieia was catharsis, or purification.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] It consisted of a series of cleansing baths and purgations, accompanied by a cleansing diet, which lasted several days.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] In the Asclepieion of Epidaurus, three large marble boards dated to 350 BC preserve the names, case histories, complaints, and cures of about 70 patients who came to the temple with a problem and shed it there.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] Asclepieia also became home to future physicians as well.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] Hippocrates is said to have received his medical training at an asclepieion on the isle of Kos.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] Prior to becoming the personal physician to the Roman Emperor Marcus Aurelius, Galen treated and studied at the famed asclepieion at Pergamon.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] In Greek mythology and religion, Asclepius was the god of medicine – son of the god Apollo and mortal Coronis.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] It is said that he was so named as a result of his mother's childbirth experience, during which time her womb had to be cut open in order for Asclepius to be born (now known as a cesarean section).
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] In Homer's *Iliad*, Asclepius was a man, a physician to soldiers wounded on the battlefield at Troy.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] But by Hippocrates' day, he had become elevated to the status of a god.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] Asclepius’ father Apollo was himself a patron god of medicine.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] It was through Apollo that Chiron, the wise and peaceful centaur, learned the art of healing.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] Under Apollo's mentorship, Chiron grew in his craft so much so that Apollo himself entrusted Chiron to train his son, Asclepius.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] Through his studies, Asclepius became so deft at medicine, especially the art of surgery, that he was able to return the living from the dead.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] His abilities quickly drew attention and jealousy from the other gods.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] As one story goes, Asclepius was killed by Zeus at the request of Hades, the god of the underworld, who feared Asclepius was stealing souls away from him.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] Before his death, however, Asclepius had several children, including: Machaon, Podalirius, Hygeia, and Panacea, who themselves were regarded as highly effective healers.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] Starting around 350 BC, the cult of Asclepius became increasingly popular.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] He was admired for serving people despite their class and social status, which was not a common practice by Olympians.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] Doctors claiming to be the direct descendants of Asclepius referred to themselves as “Asclepiads.” The symbol of a snake wrapped around a staff, which is widely used by modern medical institutions, such as the American Medical Association, is modelled on the staff that Asclepius carried.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] Over 300 asclepieia have been discovered throughout ancient Greece.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] Among the most famous of the temples were Trikka, Epidaurus, island of Kos, Athens, Corinth and Pergamon.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] These temples were often located in secluded locations surrounded modern spas or mountain sanatoriums.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] These sanctuaries could attract diverse audiences for various needs other than healing, which makes these spaces more complex than merely healing spaces.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] Also characteristic of these temples were the presence of dogs and nonvenomous snakes, known as Aesculapian snake, who would frequent the halls and dormitories and who played an important role in healing activities.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] Asclepius may first have been worshipped as a hero in Trikka (modern Trikala), Thessaly, Greece.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] Ancient mythographers generally regarded Trikka as the place of Asclepius' birth, but to date archaeological excavations have yet to uncover his sanctuary there.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] Epidaurus, on the other hand, was the first place to worship Asclepius as a god, beginning sometime in the 5th century BC.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] The asclepieion at Epidaurus is both extensive and well preserved.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] There is also an asclepieion located on the south slopes of the Acropolis of Athens which dates to around 420 BC.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] Located on the Argolid plain of the east Peloponnese in Greece, Epidaurus was the main asclepieion.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] The healing temple was named after Asclepius, the son of Apollo.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] At the Epidaurus, there were various people such as physicians and priests who would assist those who sought a session of healing from these professionals.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] Patients would come pay homage to the gods by making pilgrimages to the site, performing a prayer or a sacrifice, giving monetary gifts or even sleep at the temple.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] The Epidaurus also served as a sanctuary for those who were extremely ill.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] It was eventually expanded to a one hundred eighty-room institution to house the dying and women in labour during the Roman Empire.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] Signature to asclepian medicine was its holistic approach to patient care.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] It emphasized therapy through the natural environment, hence the carefully chosen locations, as well as care for the patient's psychological and emotional states.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] By attending to these things, the patient's innate healing mechanisms were activated, which promoted recovery.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] There were two steps in order for a patient to be considered to be treated in the asclepieion.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] The first of which is the Katharsis or purification stage.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] This is when a patient undergoes a series of baths and other methods of purging, such as a clean diet over a series of several days or purging their emotions through art.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] The patient would then make an offering such as money or a prayer to the temple, therefore to Asclepius.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] The priest of the temple then gives the patient a prayer in which it would ease the patient's mind and create a more positive outlook for them.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] Afterwards, comes incubation or dream therapy.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] Patients would sleep in the “Abaton” or “Enkoimeterion,” which was a dormitory located in the asclepieion.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] Here, they would be lulled into a hypnotic state, and begin their dream journey.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] As they slept, they were visited by Asclepius or his daughters Hygeia and Panacea.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] These dream visitations were prognostic in nature, revealing the projected course of the disease and ultimate patient outcomes.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] During this time, patients would also discover what it was they needed to do once they woke in order to treat their disease.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] Upon awakening, the patient would recount their dream to a temple priest, who would then prescribe a treatment based on their interpretation.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] Other dreams were less direct, and more symbolic.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] The physician - priests at the Asclepions were also master dream interpreters who would divine the treatment to be followed from the patient's account of the dream.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] The god Asclepius had certain totem animals in whose guise he liked to visit the supplicants as they slept.
[src:children-s-hospital/asclepeion] These were the dog, the rooster, and of course, the snake.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The ancestors of Aboriginal Australians began arriving from Southeast Asia 50,000 to 65,000 years ago, during the Last Glacial Period.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] By the time of British settlement, Aboriginal Australians spoke more than 250 distinct languages and had one of the oldest living cultures in the world.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Australia's written history commenced with Dutch exploration of most of the coastline in the 17th century.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] British colonisation began in 1788 with the establishment of the penal colony of New South Wales.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] By the mid-19th century, most of the continent had been explored by European settlers and five additional self-governing British colonies were established, each gaining responsible government by 1890.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The colonies federated in 1901, forming the Commonwealth of Australia.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] This continued a process of increasing autonomy from the United Kingdom, highlighted by the *Statute of Westminster Adoption Act 1942*, and culminating in the *Australia Act 1986*.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Australia is a parliamentary democracy with a constitutional monarchy, and a federation comprising six states and ten territories.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Its population of almost 29 million is highly urbanised and heavily concentrated on the eastern seaboard.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Canberra is the nation's capital, while its most populous cities are Sydney and Melbourne, each with a population of more than five million.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Australia's culture is diverse, and the country has one of the highest foreign-born populations in the world.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] It has a highly developed economy and one of the highest per capita incomes globally.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Its abundant natural resources and well-developed international trade relations are crucial to the country's economy.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] It ranks highly for quality of life, health, education, economic freedom, civil liberties and political rights.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Australia is a middle power, and has the world's thirteenth-highest military expenditure.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] It is a member of international groups including: the United Nations, the G20, the OECD, the World Trade Organization, Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation, the Pacific Islands Forum, the Pacific Community and the Commonwealth of Nations.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Australia also participates in the defence, intelligence and security alliances ANZUS, AUKUS and Five Eyes.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] It is a major non-NATO ally of the United States.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The name *Australia* (pronounced /əˈstreɪliə/ in Australian English) is derived from the Latin *Terra Australis Incognita* ('unknown southern land'), a name used for a hypothetical continent in the Southern Hemisphere since ancient times.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Several 16th-century cartographers used the word *Australia* on maps, but not to identify modern Australia.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] When the Dutch began visiting and mapping Australia in the 17th century, they called the continent *New Holland*.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The name *Australia* was popularised by the explorer Matthew Flinders, who circumnavigated the continent in 1803.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] However, when his account of his voyage was published in 1814, the name *Terra Australis* was used.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Governor of New South Wales Lachlan Macquarie officially recommended the name *Australia* to replace *New Holland* in December 1817.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The British Admiralty adopted the name in 1824, and the British Parliament used it in legislation in 1828.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The United Kingdom Hydrographic Office used the new name in *The Australia Directory* of 1830.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The name "Commonwealth of Australia" for the new federation of the six former colonies was formalised in the *Commonwealth of Australia Constitution Act 1900* (UK).
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Colloquial names for Australia include "Oz", "Straya" and "Down Under".
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Human habitation of the Australian continent is estimated to have begun 50,000 to 65,000 years ago, with the migration of people by land bridges and short sea crossings from what is now Southeast Asia.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] It is uncertain how many waves of immigration may have contributed to these ancestors of modern Aboriginal Australians.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The Madjedbebe rock shelter in Arnhem Land is possibly the oldest site showing the presence of humans in Australia.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The oldest human remains found are the Lake Mungo remains, which have been dated to approximately 42,000 years ago.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Aboriginal Australian culture is one of the oldest continuous cultures on Earth.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] At the time of first European contact, Aboriginal Australians belonged to wide range of societies, with diverse economies spread across at least 250 different language groups.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Estimates of the Aboriginal population before British settlement range from 300,000 to 3 million.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Aboriginal Australians cultures were (and remain) deeply connected with the land and the environment, with stories of The Dreaming maintained through oral tradition, songs, dance and paintings.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Certain groups engaged in fire-stick farming, fish farming, and built semi-permanent shelters.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] These practices have variously been characterised as "hunter-gatherer", "agricultural", "natural cultivation" and "intensification".
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Torres Strait Islander people first settled their islands at least 2,500 years ago.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Culturally and linguistically distinct from mainland Aboriginal peoples, they were seafarers and obtained their livelihood from seasonal horticulture and the resources of their reefs and seas.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Agriculture also developed on some islands and villages appeared by the 1300s.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] By the mid-18th century in northern Australia, contact, trade and cross-cultural engagement had been established between local Aboriginal groups and Makassan trepangers, visiting from present-day Indonesia.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] In 1606 the crew of the Dutch ship, *Duyfken*, captained by Willem Janszoon, made the first documented European landing in Australia and contact with Aboriginal Australians.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Later that year, Luís Vaz de Torres sailed to the north of Australia through Torres Strait, along New Guinea's southern coast.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Abel Tasman's voyage of 1642 was the first known European expedition to reach Van Diemen's Land.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] On his second voyage of 1644, he mapped the north coast of Australia south of New Guinea.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Following Tasman's voyages, the Dutch were able to make almost complete maps of Australia's northern and western coasts and much of its southern and south-eastern Tasmanian coasts.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] In 1770, Captain James Cook sailed along and mapped the east coast, which he named "New South Wales" and claimed for Great Britain.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] In 1786, the British government announced its intention to establish a penal colony in New South Wales.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] On 26 January 1788, the First Fleet commanded by Captain Arthur Phillip, arrived at Sydney Cove, Port Jackson.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] A camp was established and the Union Flag raised and the date later became Australia's national day.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Most early settlers were convicts, transported for petty crimes and assigned as labourers or servants to "free settlers" (willing immigrants).
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Once emancipated, convicts tended to integrate into colonial society.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Aboriginal resistance, convict rebellions and bushranging were sometimes suppressed under martial law.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The 1808 Rum Rebellion, carried out by officers of the New South Wales Corp, led to a temporary military junta.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] During the next two decades, social and economic reforms, together with the establishment of a Legislative Council and Supreme Court, saw the penal colony transition to a civil society.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The indigenous population declined for 150 years following European settlement, mainly due to infectious disease.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] British colonial authorities did not sign any treaties with Aboriginal groups.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] As settlement expanded, tens of thousands of Indigenous people and thousands of settlers were killed in frontier conflicts, which many historians argue included acts of genocide by settlers.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Settlers dispossessed surviving Indigenous peoples of most of their land.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] In 1803, a settlement was established in Van Diemen's Land (present-day Tasmania), and in 1813, Gregory Blaxland, William Lawson and William Wentworth crossed the Blue Mountains west of Sydney, opening the interior to European settlement.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The British claim was extended to the whole Australian continent in 1827 when Major Edmund Lockyer established a settlement on King George Sound (modern-day Albany).
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The Swan River Colony (present-day Perth) was established in 1829, evolving into the largest Australian colony by area, Western Australia.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Separate colonies were carved from New South Wales: Tasmania in 1825, South Australia in 1836, Victoria in 1851, and Queensland in 1859.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] South Australia and Victoria were founded as free colonies – they never accepted transported convicts.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Growing opposition to the convict system culminated in its abolition in the eastern colonies by the 1850s.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Initially a free colony, Western Australia accepted convicts from 1850 to 1868.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The six colonies individually gained responsible government between 1855 and 1890, managing most of their own affairs while remaining part of the British Empire.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The Colonial Office in London retained control of some matters, notably foreign affairs.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The colonial parliaments progressively extended voting rights to adult men from 1856, with women's suffrage on equal terms following between the 1890s and 1900s.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Some colonies introduced racial restrictions on voting from 1885.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] In the mid-19th century, explorers such as Burke and Wills charted Australia's interior.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] A series of gold rushes beginning in the early 1850s led to an influx of new migrants from China, North America and continental Europe, as well as outbreaks of bushranging and civil unrest; the latter peaked in 1854 when Ballarat miners launched the Eureka Rebellion against gold licence fees.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The 1860s saw the rise of blackbirding, where South Sea Islanders were coerced or abducted into indentured labour, mainly by Queensland colonists.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] From 1886, Australian colonial governments began removing many Aboriginal children from their families and communities, justified on the grounds of child protection and forced assimilation policies.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The Second Boer War (1899–1902) marked the largest overseas deployment of Australia's colonial forces.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] On 1 January 1901, federation of the colonies was achieved after a decade of planning, constitutional conventions and referendums, resulting in the establishment of the Commonwealth of Australia as a nation under the new Australian Constitution.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] From 1901, Australia was a self-governing dominion within the British Empire.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] It was one of the founding members of the League of Nations in 1920, and the United Nations in 1945.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The *Statute of Westminster 1931* ended the ability of the UK to legislate for Australia at the federal level without Australia's consent.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Australia adopted it in 1942, but it was backdated to 1939 to confirm the validity of legislation passed during World War II.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The Australian Capital Territory was formed in 1911 as the location for the future federal capital of Canberra.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] While it was being constructed, Melbourne served as the temporary capital from 1901 to 1927.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The Northern Territory was transferred from South Australia to the Commonwealth in 1911.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Australia took over the administration of the Territory of Papua (previously British New Guinea) in 1905 and of the Territory of New Guinea (formerly German New Guinea) in 1920.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The two were unified as the Territory of Papua and New Guinea in 1949 and gained independence from Australia in 1975.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] In 1914, Australia joined the Allies in the First World War, and took part in the fighting on several fronts.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Of the 324,000 men who served overseas, about 60,000 were killed and another 152,000 were wounded.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Many Australians regard the defeat of the Australian and New Zealand Army Corps (ANZAC) at Gallipoli in 1915 as the "baptism of fire" that forged the new nation's identity.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The beginning of the campaign is commemorated annually on Anzac Day, a date which rivals Australia Day as the nation's most important.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] From 1939 to 1945, Australia joined the Allies in fighting the Second World War.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Australia's armed forces fought in the Pacific, European and Mediterranean and Middle East theatres.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Since 1951, Australia has maintained a mutual security alliance with the United States under the ANZUS treaty.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] In the three decades following World War II, Australia experienced significant increases in living standards, leisure time and suburban development.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Governments encouraged a large wave of immigration from across Europe and called these migrants "New Australians".
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] High immigration was justified to Australians using the slogan "populate or perish", and from the 1960s the white Australia policy was gradually relaxed.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] A member of the Western Bloc during the Cold War, Australia participated in the Korean War and the Malayan Emergency during the 1950s and the Vietnam War from 1962 to 1973.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Tensions over communist influence in society led to unsuccessful attempts by the Menzies Government to ban the Communist Party of Australia, and a bitter split in the Labor Party in 1955.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] As a result of a 1967 referendum, the federal government gained the power to legislate with regard to Aboriginal Australians, and Aboriginal Australians were fully included in the census.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Pre-colonial land interests (referred to as native title in Australia) was recognised in law for the first time when the High Court of Australia held in *Mabo v Queensland (No 2)* that Australia was not *terra nullius* ('land belonging to no one') at the time of European settlement.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Following the abolition of the last vestiges of the White Australia policy in 1973, Australia's demography and culture transformed as a result of a large and ongoing wave of non-European immigration, mostly from Asia.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The late 20th century also saw an increasing focus on foreign policy ties with other Asia–Pacific nations.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The Australia Acts of 1986 severed the remaining constitutional ties between Australia and the United Kingdom while maintaining the monarch in her independent capacity as Queen of Australia.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] In a 1999 constitutional referendum, 55% of voters rejected abolishing the monarchy and becoming a republic.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Following the September 11 attacks in the United States, Australia joined the United States in fighting the Afghanistan War from 2001 to 2021 and the Iraq War from 2003 to 2009.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The nation's trade relations also became increasingly oriented towards East Asia in the 21st century, with China becoming the nation's largest trading partner by a large margin.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] In response to the COVID-19 pandemic, from March 2020 lockdowns and other restrictions on public gatherings and movement across the national and state borders were implemented by the Federal, state and territory governments.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Following the rollout of vaccines in 2021, these restrictions were gradually eased.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] In October 2023, Australia declared that COVID-19 was no longer a communicable disease incident of national significance.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Australia consists of the mainland Australian continent, the island of Tasmania, numerous smaller offshore islands, and the remote offshore territories of Ashmore and Cartier Islands, Christmas Island, Cocos (Keeling) Islands, Coral Sea Islands, Heard and McDonald Islands, and Norfolk Island.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Australia also claims about 42% of Antarctica as the Australian Antarctic Territory, but this claim is only recognised by four other countries.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Mainland Australia lies between latitudes 9° and 44° south, and longitudes 112° and 154° east.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Surrounded by the Indian and Pacific oceans, Australia is separated from Asia by the Arafura and Timor seas, with the Coral Sea lying off the Queensland coast, and the Tasman Sea lying between Australia and New Zealand.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The Great Barrier Reef, the world's largest coral reef, lies a short distance off the north-east coast and extends for more than 2,300 km (1,400 mi).
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The mainland is the world's smallest continent and the country is the sixth-largest by total area.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Australia is sometimes considered the world's largest island and is often dubbed the "island continent".
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] It has 35,877 km (22,293 mi) of coastline (excluding all offshore islands), and claims an exclusive economic zone of 8,148,250 square kilometres (3,146,060 sq mi).
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] This exclusive economic zone does not include the Australian Antarctic Territory.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] In 2021, Australia had 10% of the global permanent meadows and pastureland.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Forest cover is about 17% of Australia's land area.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The Australian mainland is relatively flat, with an average height of 325 metres (1,066 ft) compared with 870 metres (2,850 ft) for all continents.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The Great Dividing Range runs along most of eastern Australia, dividing the central lowlands from the eastern highlands.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] At 2,228 m (7,310 ft), Mount Kosciuszko is the highest mountain on the mainland.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Taller are Mawson Peak, at 2,745 m (9,006 ft), on Heard Island, and, in the Australian Antarctic Territory, Mount McClintock and Mount Menzies, at 3,492 m (11,457 ft) and 3,355 m (11,007 ft) respectively.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The Murray-Darling is the major river system, draining most of inland New South Wales and Southern Queensland towards Lake Alexandrina and the sea in South Australia.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] There are also smaller coastal river systems, inland drainage systems such as the Lake Eyre system, and salt lake systems in central and western Australia.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Australia's rivers have the lowest discharge into the sea of any continent.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The mainland's flat, arid profile also makes its rivers slow-moving, resulting in a build up of salt on the land.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Salinisation adversely affects Australia's soil which is, on average, poor in nutrients compared with world standards.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Australia's population is concentrated on the coastal fringes.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] About 95% of the population lives within 100 km of the coast; the world average is 39%.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Australia's population density is 3.5 inhabitants per square kilometre, which is one of the lowest in the world.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] However, there is a large concentration of the population in cities along the temperate south-eastern coastline, and population density exceeds 38 inhabitants per square kilometre in central Melbourne.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Formerly part of the Rodinia and Gondwana supercontinents, Australia completely separated from Antarctica about 35 million years ago and continued drifting northwards.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] When the Last Glacial Period ended, rising sea levels separated the Australian mainland from New Guinea about 8,000 years ago and from Tasmania about 6,000 years ago.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Australia lies well within the Australian tectonic plate.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The mainland is relatively stable geologically, with no major mountain building, active volcanoes or tectonic faults.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] However, the Australian plate is moving north-northeast at a rate of about 6 to 7 cm a year and is currently in collision with the Eurasian plate and Pacific plate.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The resulting intratectonic stresses lead to relatively high seismic activity for a geologically stable landmass.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] There were 18 earthquakes with a moment magnitude of greater than 6 between 1901 and 2017.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The Newcastle earthquake of 1989 was Australia's deadliest, killing 13 people.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] There were active volcanoes on the eastern mainland as recently as 4,600 years ago, and this is reflected in Aboriginal place names and creation stories.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Currently, volcanism occurs in the remote Heard Island and McDonald Islands.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The Australian continental crust was created in three cycles from the oldest Archaean cratons in the west to the younger orogenic formations in the east (built about 541 million to 252 million years ago).
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The oldest Australian surface rocks date to the Archaean period.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Some in Western Australia are older than 3.7 billion years and others in South Australia are over 3.1 billion years old.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The oldest zircon crystals on Earth, dating back 4.4 billion years, have been found in Western Australia.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] However, about 80 per cent of Australia is covered by sedimentary rocks and regolith that are less than 250 million years old.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The Australian climate ranges from wet tropical in the northeast and northwest to arid in the centre.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The coastal south is temperate and humid with winter freezing and snow in the southeastern highlands and Tasmania.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The climate is influenced by Australia's position in the "horse latitudes", which tends to bring arid conditions.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Overall, the Australian mainland is the driest inhabited continent, with an average annual rainfall of 470 millimetres (19 in).
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] About 70% of the country is arid or semi-arid, and about 18% is desert.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The climate is also influenced by various systems such as the El Niño–Southern Oscillation, the Indian Ocean Dipole and the Southern Annular Mode.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Australia has unusual variability in rainfall within years and between years, leading to frequent droughts and flooding.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Cyclones and rain depressions are common in tropical Australia.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The summer monsoon brings significant rainfall to northern Australia and low pressure cells bring winter rainfall in the south.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The hottest regions are in the northwest of the country and the coolest in the southeast.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Bushfire conditions are common in southern Australia.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Climate change from increased greenhouse gas emissions has led to a 1.5 °C rise in Australian temperatures since 1910 and an increase in extreme heat and heavy rainfall events.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] There has been a reduction in rainfall from April to October in southern Australia since 1970 and a longer bushfire season since the 1950s.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Rainfall has increased in northern Australia since the 1970s.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The number of tropical cyclones has fallen since 1982 and alpine snow has decreased since the late 1950s.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Sea levels are rising around Australia and the surrounding oceans are becoming more acidic.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Australia is one of 17 megadiverse countries.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Because of its long geographic isolation, much of Australia's biota is unique.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] About 94% of its amphibians, 93% of its reptiles and flowering plants, 69% of its mammals and 46% of its birds are endemic.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Australia has a wide range of ecosystems of which 89 regions and 419 subregions are recognised in the Australian bioregion framework.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] In January 2025, there were 168,386 named species on the Australian National Species List.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] However, it is estimated that 70% of Australian species have not been discovered and classified and that there may be 600,000 Australian native species.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] In general, knowledge of vertebrates and flowering plants is better than for invertebrates and fungi.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] It is estimated that less that 10% of Australia's fungi and insects have been named.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] About 10% of the world's known plant species are found in Australia.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Many of these have adapted to the arid climate, variable rainfall and nutrient-poor soil.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Deserts and xeric shrubland cover about 70% of the mainland.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Acacia, banksia and eucalypts have spread over much of Australia.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Many plants have hard and long-living leaves, and are rich in carbon, poor in nutrients, and well adapted to bushfires.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] About two-thirds of the world's 330 species of marsupials are native to Australia.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Australian placental mammals (overwhelmingly bats, rats and mice) also make up almost 47% of the world's land mammal species.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Australia has about 10% of the world's known reptile species.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] There are also about 320,500 invertebrate species, of which insects are the largest class, accounting for more than 75% of all animal species.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Australia has over 15,000 known species of fungi, although it is possible that tens of thousands more exist.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Australia's wildlife show many adaptations to their environments.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] As the leaves of most plants are poor in nutrients, Australia has a high proportion of birds, insects and marsupials, such as the honey possum, that feed on nectar and pollen.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The koala is an exception, specialising in feeding on eucalyptus leaves.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Nutritionally poor flora and variable rainfall also favour animals with lower energy requirements, including snakes, lizards, and hopping marsupials such as the kangaroo and wallaby.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] There is, however, evidence of convergent evolution of Australia's marsupials and the placental mammals of other continents living in similar environments.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] For example, the extinct thylacine (Tasmanian tiger) had similarities with the placental wolf, marsupial moles with the golden moles of Africa, and hopping mice with the hopping rodents of other arid regions.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] There were major extinctions of Australia's vertebrates, including its megafauna, about 46 thousand years ago, and there is an ongoing scientific debate over the role of human activity and climate change in these extinctions.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The contraction of the range of the Tasmanian tiger and Tasmanian devil to that island about 4,000 to 5,000 years ago is also consistent with changes on the mainland including an increasing human population, the introduction of the dingo, and the greater use of fire and new stone tool technologies.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Over the past two centuries, Australia has lost more mammal species than any other continent.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Overall, 100 Australian species are listed as extinct or extinct in the wild.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] In June 2021, over 1,000 animal and plant species were listed by Australian governments as endangered or critically endangered.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The major threats to endangered species are landscape change, ecosystem disruption, introduced species such as the feral cat and red fox, and climate change.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The federal *Environment Protection and Biodiversity Conservation Act 1999* is the legal framework for the protection of threatened species.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The National Reserve System is Australia's network of protected areas.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] As at 30 June 2022, it covered over 22% of Australia's land mass.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] *Australia's Strategy for Nature 2024–2030* is the national biodiversity plan that aims to reverse biodiversity loss in Australia by 2030 and meet the county's obligations under the United Nations Convention on Biological Diversity and other international agreements.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Australia is a constitutional monarchy, a parliamentary democracy and a federation.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The country has maintained its mostly unchanged constitution alongside a stable liberal democratic political system since Federation in 1901.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] It is one of the world's oldest federations, in which power is divided between the federal and state governments.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Following elections on 3 May 2025, the prime minister is Anthony Albanese of the Australian Labor Party.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Charles III reigns as King of Australia and is represented in Australia by the governor-general at the federal level and by the governors at the state level, who by section 63 of the Constitution and convention act on the advice of their ministers.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Thus, in practice the governor-general acts as a legal figurehead for the actions of the prime minister and the Cabinet.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The governor-general may in some situations exercise reserve powers: powers exercisable in the absence of, or contrary to, ministerial advice.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] When these powers may be exercised is governed by convention and their precise scope is unclear.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The most notable exercise of these powers was the dismissal of the Whitlam government in the constitutional crisis of 1975.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] In the Senate (the upper house), there are 76 senators: twelve each from the states and two each from the mainland territories (the Australian Capital Territory and the Northern Territory).
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The House of Representatives (the lower house) has 150 members elected from single-member electoral divisions, commonly known as "electorates" or "seats", allocated to states on the basis of population, with each of the current states guaranteed a minimum of five seats.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The lower house has a maximum term of three years, but this is not fixed and governments usually dissolve the house early for an election at some point in the 6 months before the maximum.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Elections for both chambers are generally held simultaneously with senators having overlapping six-year terms except for those from the territories, whose terms are not fixed but are tied to the electoral cycle for the lower house.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Thus, only 40 of the 76 places in the Senate are put to each election unless the cycle is interrupted by a double dissolution.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Australia's electoral system uses preferential voting for the House of Representatives and all state and territory lower house elections (with the exception of Tasmania and the ACT which use the Hare-Clark system).
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The Senate and most state upper houses use the proportional system which combines preferential voting with proportional representation for each state.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Voting and enrolment is compulsory for all enrolled citizens 18 years and older in every jurisdiction.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The party with majority support in the House of Representatives forms the government and its leader becomes prime minister.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The governor-general appoints the prime minister and may dismiss one who has lost the confidence of parliament or acts illegally.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] As Australia is a Westminster parliamentary democracy with a powerful and elected upper house, its system has sometimes been called a "Washminster mutation", or semi-parliamentary.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] There are two major political groups that have usually formed government federally: the Australian Labor Party and the Coalition which is a grouping of the Liberal Party and its minor partner, the National Party.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Within Australian political culture, the Labor Party is considered centre-left and the Coalition is considered centre-right.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Independent members and several minor parties have achieved representation in Australian parliaments, mostly in upper houses.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The Australian Greens have been the third largest party by both vote and membership since 2004.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Australia has six states – New South Wales (NSW), Victoria (Vic), Queensland (Qld), Western Australia (WA), South Australia (SA) and Tasmania (Tas) – and two mainland self-governing territories – the Australian Capital Territory (ACT) and the Northern Territory (NT).
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The states have the general power to make laws except in the few areas where the constitution grants the Commonwealth (the federal level of government) exclusive powers.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The Commonwealth can only make laws on topics listed in the constitution but its laws prevail over those of the states to the extent of any inconsistency.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Since Federation, the Commonwealth's power relative to the states has significantly increased due to the increasingly wide interpretation given to listed Commonwealth powers – and because of the states' heavy financial reliance on Commonwealth grants.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Each state and major mainland territory has its own parliament – unicameral in the Northern Territory, the ACT and Queensland, and bicameral in the other states.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The lower houses are known as the Legislative Assembly (the House of Assembly in South Australia and Tasmania); the upper houses are known as the Legislative Council.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The head of the government in each state is the premier and in each territory the chief minister.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The King is represented in each state by a governor.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] At the Commonwealth level, the King's representative is the governor-general.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The remote Macquarie Island and Lord Howe Island are part of Tasmania and New South Wales respectively.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Australia is a middle power, whose foreign relations has three core bi-partisan pillars: commitment to the US alliance, engagement with the Indo-Pacific and support for international institutions, rules and co-operation.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Through the ANZUS pact and its status as a major non-NATO ally, Australia maintains a close relationship with the US, which encompasses strong defence, security and trade ties.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] In the Indo-Pacific, the country seeks to increase its trade ties through the open flow of trade and capital, while managing the rise of Chinese power by supporting the existing rules-based order.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Regionally, the country is a member of the Pacific Islands Forum, the Pacific Community, the ASEAN+6 mechanism and the East Asia Summit.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Internationally, the country is a member of the United Nations (of which it was a founding member), the Commonwealth of Nations, the OECD and the G20.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] This reflects the country's generally strong commitment to multilateralism.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Australia has pursued the cause of international trade liberalisation.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] It led the formation of the Cairns Group and Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation, and is a member of the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) and the World Trade Organization (WTO).
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Australia maintains a deeply integrated relationship with neighbouring New Zealand, with free mobility of citizens between the two countries under the Trans-Tasman Travel Arrangement and free trade under the Closer Economic Relations agreement.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The most favourably viewed countries by the Australian people in 2021 include New Zealand, the United Kingdom, Japan, Germany, Taiwan, Thailand, the United States and South Korea.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] It also maintains an international aid program under which some 75 countries receive assistance.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Australia ranked fourth in the Center for Global Development's 2021 Commitment to Development Index.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The power over foreign policy is highly concentrated in the prime minister and the national security committee, with major decision such as joining the 2003 invasion of Iraq made without prior Cabinet approval.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Similarly, the Parliament does not play a formal role in foreign policy and the power to declare war lies solely with the executive government.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade supports the executive in its policy decisions.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The two main institutions involved in the management of Australia's armed forces are the Australian Defence Force (ADF) and the Department of Defence, together known as "Defence".
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The Australian Defence Force is the military wing, headed by the chief of the defence force, and contains three branches: the Royal Australian Navy, the Australian Army and the Royal Australian Air Force.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] In 2021, it had 84,865 currently serving personnel (including 60,286 regulars and 24,581 reservists).
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The Department of Defence is the civilian wing and is headed by the secretary of defence.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] These two leaders collective manage Defence as a diarchy, with shared and joint responsibilities.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The titular role of commander-in-chief is held by the governor-general; however, actual command is vested in the chief of the Defence Force.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The executive branch of the Commonwealth government has overall control of the military through the minister of defence, who is subject to the decisions of Cabinet and its National Security Committee.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Major Australian intelligence agencies include the Australian Secret Intelligence Service (foreign intelligence), the Australian Signals Directorate (signals intelligence) and the Australian Security Intelligence Organisation (domestic security).
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] In 2022, defence spending was 1.9% of GDP, representing the world's 13th-largest defence budget.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Australia has generally strong protections for civil and political rights, and the country has signed up to a wide range of international rights treaties.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Important documents protecting human rights include the Constitution, the *Racial Discrimination Act 1975*, the *Sex Discrimination Act 1984*, the *Disability Discrimination Act 1992*, and the *Age Discrimination Act 2004*.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Same-sex marriage has been legal in the nation since 2017.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Unlike other comparable Western democracies, Australia does not have a single federal charter of rights in the Constitution or under legislation; however, the ACT, Victoria, and Queensland have state-based ones.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] International organisations such as Human Rights Watch and Amnesty International have expressed concerns in areas including asylum-seeker policy, Indigenous deaths in custody, the lack of entrenched rights protection, and laws restricting protesting.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Australia's mixed-market economy is highly developed and rich in natural resources.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] It is the world's twelfth largest by nominal terms, and the twenty-third largest by PPP.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] As of 2021, Australia has the second-highest amount of wealth per adult, after Luxembourg, and the thirteenth-highest financial assets per capita, as well as one of the highest per capita incomes globally.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] It has a labour force of some 13.5 million, with an unemployment rate of 3.5% as of June 2022.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] According to the Australian Council of Social Service, the poverty rate of Australia exceeds 13.6% of the population, encompassing over 3.2 million.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] It also estimated that there were 774,000 (17.7%) children under the age of 15 living in relative poverty.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The Australian dollar is the national currency, which is also used by three island states in the Pacific: Kiribati, Nauru, and Tuvalu.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Australian government debt, about $963 billion in June 2022, exceeds 45.1% of the country's total GDP, and is the world's eighth-highest.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Australia had the second-highest level of household debt in the world in 2020, after Switzerland.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Its house prices are among the highest in the world, especially in the large urban areas.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The large service sector accounts for about 71.2% of total GDP, followed by the industrial sector (25.3%), while its agriculture sector makes up 3.6% of total GDP.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Australia is the world's 21st-largest exporter and 24th-largest importer.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] China is Australia's largest trading partner, accounting for roughly 40% of the country's exports and 17.6% of its imports.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Other major export markets include Japan, the United States, and South Korea.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Australia has high levels of competitiveness and economic freedom, and was ranked tenth in the Human Development Index in 2022.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] As of 2022, it is ranked twelfth in the Index of Economic Freedom.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] It attracted 9.5 million international tourists in 2019, and was ranked thirteenth among the countries of Asia-Pacific in 2019 for inbound tourism.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The 2021 *Travel and Tourism Competitiveness Report* ranked Australia seventh-highest in the world out of 117 countries.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Its international tourism receipts in 2019 amounted to $45.7 billion.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Total consumption of energy in this period was sourced from coal (28.4%), oil (37.3%), gas (27.4%) and renewables (7%).
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] From 2012 to 2022, the energy sourced from renewables has increased 5.7%, while energy sourced from coal has decreased 2.6%.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] The use of gas also increased by 1.5% and the use of oil stayed relatively stable with a reduction of only 0.2%.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] In 2020, Australia produced 27.7% of its electricity from renewable sources, exceeding the target set by the Commonwealth government in 2009 of 20% renewable energy by 2020.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] A new target of 82% renewable energy by 2030 was set in 2022 and a target for net zero emissions by 2050 was set in 2021.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] In 2019, Australia spent $35.6 billion on research and development, allocating about 1.79% of GDP.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] A 2022 study by the industry lobby group, The Tech Council of Australia, stated that the Australian technology sector combined contributes $167 billion a year to the economy and employs 861,000 people.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] In 2022, startup ecosystems in Sydney and Melbourne were valued at $34 billion.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Australia ranked 22nd in the Global Innovation Index 2025.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] With only 0.3% of the world's population, Australia contributed over 4% of the world's published research in 2020, making it one of the top 10 research contributors in the world.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] CSIRO, Australia's national science agency, contributes 10% of all research in the country, while the rest is carried out by universities.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Australian achievements include the invention of atomic absorption spectroscopy, the essential components of Wi-Fi technology, and the development of the first commercially successful polymer banknote.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] As of 2026, 14 Australian scientists have been awarded the Nobel Prize in physics, chemistry or medicine, and two have been awarded the Fields Medal.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p01] Facilities supporting space exploration include the Square Kilometre Array and Australia Telescope Compact Array radio telescopes, telescopes such as the Siding Spring Observatory, and ground stations such as the Canberra Deep Space Communication Complex.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p02] The population of Australia is estimated to be 27,724,744 as of September 2025.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p02] It is the 54th most populous country in the world and the most populous Oceanian country.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p02] Australia has a population density of 3.4 persons per square kilometre of total land area, which makes it one of the most sparsely populated countries in the world.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p02] The population is heavily concentrated on the east coast, and in particular in the south-eastern region between South East Queensland to the north-east and Adelaide to the south-west.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p02] Australia is also highly urbanised, with 67% of the population living in the Greater Capital City Statistical Areas (metropolitan areas of the state and mainland territorial capital cities) in 2018.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p02] Metropolitan areas with more than one million inhabitants are Sydney, Melbourne, Brisbane, Perth and Adelaide.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p02] In common with many other developed countries, Australia is experiencing a demographic shift towards an older population, with more retirees and fewer people of working age.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p02] In 2021, the average age of the population was 39 years.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p02] Australia has five cities (including their suburbs) that have populations larger than one million people.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p02] The majority of Australia's population lives near coastlines.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p02] Between 1788 and the Second World War, the vast majority of settlers and immigrants came from the British Isles (principally England, Ireland and Scotland), although Australia had significant immigration from China and Germany during the 19th century.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p02] Following Federation in 1901, the white Australia policy was strengthened, restricting further migration from these areas.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p02] However, this policy was relaxed following WW2, and in the decades following, Australia received a large wave of immigration from across Europe, with many more immigrants arriving from Southern and Eastern Europe than in previous decades.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p02] Following the end of the White Australia policy in 1973, Australia adopted multiculturalism as policy, culminating in the Racial Discrimination Act 1975.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p02] Subsequently, there has been a large and continuing wave of immigration from across the world, with Asia being the largest source of immigrants in the 21st century.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p02] Today, Australia has the world's eighth-largest immigrant population, with immigrants accounting for 30% of the population, the highest proportion among major Western nations.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p02] In 2022–23, 212,789 permanent migrants were admitted to Australia, with a net migration population gain of 518,000 people inclusive of non-permanent residents.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p02] Most entered on skilled visas, however the immigration program also offers visas for family members and refugees.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p02] The Australian Bureau of Statistics asks each Australian resident to nominate up to two ancestries each census and the responses are classified into broad ancestry groups.
[src:children-s-hospital/australia-p02] At the 2021 census, 3.8% of the Australian population identified as being Indigenous – Aboriginal Australians and Torres Strait Islanders.
